<HEADLINE> Russian President, Duma React on Ending Iraq Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
Sunday issued a statement in connection with the end to bombing
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said that "the common sense has finally won, and the
international community should draw serious conclusions from the
tragic events," the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-British airstrikes on Iraq were ordered to stop
earlier Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In his statement Yeltsin also said that "it is already clear
that the use of force complicated the solution of the Iraqi
problem."
</P>
<P>
Russia has shown once again that it is a powerful factor in the
upkeep of stability and security in the world by strong opposing
the use of force against Iraq by the U.S. and Britain, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the State Duma also positively reacted on the
termination of U.S.-British hostilities against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Duma Vice-Speaker Mikhail Gutseriyev said Sunday that the U.S.
and Britain have finally listened to the international opinion
and the stances of Russia, China and other countries opposing the
combat operation against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"The end of attacks is a positive factor," he said.
</P>
<P>
Russia has from the very start voiced its strongly negative
attitude to the use of force in the solution of the Iraqi problem
and urged the need for using only political and diplomatic methods
in settling the Iraqi crisis, Gutseriyev said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Great Britain are responsible for the death of
Iraq citizens and the suffering of civilians, women and children,
the Duma vice-speaker noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
