<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Inflation to Die in 2002: CEBR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 20 (Xinhua) -- The year 2002 will see the end
of the era of relentlessly rising prices in Britain, with the
costs of goods and services falling year on year, according to a
leading economic institute.
</P>
<P>
The Center for Economics and Business Research (CEBR) predicted
that the UK economy is about to plunge into a period of negative
inflation, or deflation, for the first time since the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
It said a recession in the UK will push underlying inflation
down from its present rate of almost 3 percent to 0.1 percent in
2001.
</P>
<P>
The following year, inflation will fall to -0.2 percent, and
then remain below zero, the CEBR added.
</P>
<P>
The institute blamed weak demand for consumer goods, firms
cutting prices to sell off unwanted stock and falling oil and
commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
Janice Clark, an economist of the CEBR, said that once the UK
slips into negative inflation, this is likely to persist for
several years.
</P>
<P>
The CEBR also scaled down its estimate for economic growth in
1999, predicting that it will contract by 0.1 percent. This is
significantly lower than the 0.4 percent growth it predicted for
1999 in its last forecast in September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
