<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Economy Most Unstable: Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Barclays bank Sunday said
Zimbabwe has the most unstable peacetime economy in the southern
African region due to continuously plummeting public and business
confidence.
</P>
<P>
In its Economic Bulletin for December released in Harare, the
bank said most households had become much poorer in the wake of a
more than 100 percent decline in the value of the exchange rate
in local currency terms, while an inflation rate of 45 percent in
November was among the highest in the region.
</P>
<P>
"This under-performance in the real economy while disturbing,
masks a much worse performance in the financial economy and the
balance of payments," Barclays said.
</P>
<P>
"The question is: can a further descent into deep recession be
avoided by arresting the fall in confidence and allowing the
tradable goods sectors to respond to the very tangible export
incentives now in place," the bank's paper said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said if this happens, it would represent the best
case scenario and yield a projected growth rate of around three
percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
But the downside alternatives appeared grim, involving a
decline into substantially negative economic growth and probably
economic "autarky".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Trying to Contain Malaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 20 (Xinhua) -- The Addis Ababa city
health bureau said Sunday that efforts are underway to contain
malaria epidemic that hit hardly some areas of Ethiopian capital
this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency, Sara Emiru, an
official of the city health bureau, said that five residential
councils of the city that were hit hardly by the epidemic were
sprayed with anti-mosquito chemical.
</P>
<P>
She said sewages and other unclean areas have provided a
fertile ground for Mosquito breeding in the areas.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the number of people suffering from
malaria has now decreased.
</P>
<P>
An estimated two million people in Ethiopia are affected by
malaria every year. As a result of changes in weather conditions
this year, traditionally safer areas including Addis Ababa which
is over 2400 meters above sea level, have been hit by malaria.
</P>
<P>
Over 75 percent of the total area of the country is suitable
for mosquito breeding and over 40 million of the total 58 million
population live in the malaria-prone localities.
</P>
<P>
A consignment of anti-malaria medicines donated by the World
Health Organization (WHO) has already arrived at Addis Ababa
airport where it is due to be distributed to all parts of the
country, according to an earlier announcement from the
government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
