<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10,000 Jordanians Stage Anti-U.S. Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Some 10,000 Jordanians staged
protest against the U.S.-British air strikes on Iraq in Amman
Sunday afternoon, and called for lifting the eight-year-old
U.N. sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Demonstrators, waving flags and chanting slogans, condemned the
attacks on Iraq which came to an end Sunday morning and called the
United Nations to lift what they said unjust sanctions on Iraq
imposed since the 1991 Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
The protesters also blamed the United States for applying
double standards in tackling world issues in the rally, which was
organized by the non-governmental Popular Committee for
Supporting Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government, which had earlier turned down
requests by opposition parities to stage anti-U.S. demonstrations,
apparently gave green light to the protest rallies on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
No clashes were reported so far.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Sunday, deputies of the Lower House also condemned the
air attacks on Iraq, called the United Nations to lift its
sanctions on Iraq and send medical teams to Baghdad to treat
the injured.
</P>
<P>
The Jordan government has also called for intensified
diplomatic efforts to put an end to the ongoing Iraqi crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
