<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran will hold a trade fair in Jeddah, Saudi Arabia
for the first time from February 28 to March 5.
</P>
<P>
Director of the fair Ali Asghar Oqabi said Sunday that the
trade fair staged in Jeddah will be co-sponsored by the Export
Promotion Center of Iran and a group of Iranian businessman in
line with Tehran's policy of expanding trade ties with Saudi
Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Goods to be on display include foodstuff, dried fruit,
garments, handicrafts, carpets, industrial and mineral products,
and some of them will be sold during the fair.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt will get a grant of 20 million Egyptian pounds
(5.88 million U.S. dollars) from Denmark, the Egyptian Gazette
newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Under a deal signed between the two countries, the money will
be used in a program to develop Egypt's southern governorates.
</P>
<P>
The fund is aimed at improving the supply of potable water by
the Aswan Water Authority to remote rural areas and formulating a
plan to upgrade the sewerage networks in Aswan, a town of 700
kilometers south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Denmark has granted Egypt a total of 308 million pounds (90.59
million dollars) in recent years, which have gone to Egypt's water,
energy and environmental protection projects.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE) has planned to
hold a consumer goods exhibition in the country's capital of Abu Dhabi to
mark the Holy Month of Ramadan, the Gulf News daily reported on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition was co-sponsored by the Abu Dhabi Chamber of
Commerce and the UAE Red Crescent Society. It will be held at the
Abu Dhabi International Exhibition Center from December 26 to
January 14 .
</P>
<P>
Around 13 countries and regions, including Oman, Saudi
Arabia, Yemen, Syria, Morocco, Egypt, Jordan, India, Pakistan,
France, will participate in the exhibition.  
</P>
</TEXT>
