<HEADLINE> Russian FM Urges Assessment of U.S.-British Raids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Russia objects to the turning
of the U.S.-British military action against Iraq into "a rule of
international conduct," Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said
Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
The United Nation should make an assessment of the U.S. and
British missile strikes on Iraq, Ivanov said in an interview with
the Russian Public RTR TV company on the Zerkalo (Mirror) program.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov noted that if no worthy assessment of the move is now
given, if similar actions will not be prevented through possible
efforts in future, such actions can "become a rule of
international conduct." That is the danger of the situation that
shaped up as a result of the new Iraqi crisis, he added.
</P>
<P>
Russia is strongly against such developments around Iraq, said
Ivanov. He said it is no longer a question of Iraq but it is a
global question.
</P>
<P>
"It is not a matter of confrontation, but a matter of future
fundamentals of the world order."
</P>
<P>
"Even in the most complex Cold War times, the U.N. Charter was
unbroken" in contrast to the way it has been broken during the
current Gulf crisis, the minister stressed.
</P>
<P>
The moves of the United States and Great Britain were not
supported in Russia. "They were denounced by all power branches,
everyone spoke from coordinated and firm positions," Ivanov said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
