<HEADLINE> Iraq Says Military Attack Causes Thousands of Casualties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Nizar Hamdoon, Iraq's
ambassador to the United Nations, said Sunday that the U.S.-led
military strikes against Iraq killed or wounded thousands of
people.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Hamdoon said, "There has been enormous
damage, mainly to the civilian infrastructure and to human life. I
am told that the casualties are in thousands, in terms of people
who were killed or wounded. But we do not have any final figures."
</P>
<P>
Hamdoon said Iraq would ask the United Nations Security Council
to lift immediately the economic sanctions which had been in place
for eight years.
</P>
<P>
"We think we deserve it," the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
Hamdoon stressed that Iraq could no longer work with Executive
Chairman of the U.N. Special Commission Richard Butler.
</P>
<P>
"I do not think there is any possibility of that. Butler was
coordinating and conspiring together with people in the U.S.
administration here to try to bomb Iraq and to provide the pretext
for that," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
