<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish PM-Designate Returns Mandate for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister
designate Bulent Ecevit returned his mandate for government
formation to President Suleyman Demirel Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Demirel at the presidential palace, Ecevit,
also leader of the Democratic Left Party (DSP), told reporters
that "I told the president that I have been unable to fulfill my
duty."
</P>
<P>
"I have tried all the ways and choices that are
possible except a government formula including the Virtue Party
(FP), " he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Ecevit promised that his party will cooperate with the
new government once it is formed.
</P>
<P>
He said Turkey is confronted with serious problems both at home
and abroad, adding a government should be formed without delay.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Demirel is meeting with political party leaders in
a bid to name another candidate to fulfill the task.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit was assigned by Demirel to form a 56th coalition
government on December 2 following the collapse of the minority
government led by Mesut Yilmaz for his corruption scandal on
November 25.
</P>
<P>
Despite Ecevit's 20-day tour of the political parties in
the parliament, his efforts fell short of coming up with a
government formula that could pass a vote of confidence in the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The True Path Party (DYP) and the Republican People's Party
(CHP) had rejected a proposal for a coalition to be formed by the
Motherland Party (ANAP), the DYP and the DSP, a proposal for the
DSP minority government and another proposal for the broad-based
government.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish constitution requires a designated prime minister
to form a new government within 45 days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
