<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKFE Successful in Managing Risks in Extreme Volatility in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Futures
Exchange (HKFE) has been successful in 1998 in particular in the
way it managed the risks associated with extreme volatility, HKFE
Chief Executive Randy Gilmore said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The markets have experienced great volatility and large trading
volume in 1998 but the exchange has been successful in ensuring
the safe, fair and orderly operation of the markets, Gilmore said.
</P>
<P>
The volatility of the Hang Seng Index was high, ranging from
the year high so far of 11,810 points on March 25 to the year low
of 6,660 points on August 13.
</P>
<P>
Intra-day volatility of Hang Seng Index futures (spot month) in
1998 up to the present was greatest on February 2 with a range of
1,040 points. The busiest day for the product in the year so far
was May 27 with a total of 73,957 contracts traded.
</P>
<P>
Hang Seng Index futures has continued to be the exchange's
flagship product, with 6,557,760 contracts traded during the year,
up to November 30, 1998, Gilmore said.
</P>
<P>
However, Gilmore said that the biggest achievement for the
exchange in 1998 is the building of the senior management team. He
says that as a result of the management reorganization, the
exchange has recruited talents from different backgrounds to drive
the exchange business.
</P>
<P>
In the forefront of issues facing exchanges all around the
world are the questions of globalization and whether or not they
should change over to screen-based trading, Gilmore said.
</P>
<P>
Upgrading and ensuring the robustness of the Automated Trading
System (ATS) has been the biggest challenge for HKFE in 1998,
Gilmore said. The exchange decided at the end of 1997 to migrate
the Hang Seng Index futures and options contracts to electronic
trading within a 24-month time frame.
</P>
<P>
The advantages of electronic trading are efficiency, an audit
trail and cost effectiveness, Gilmore said. It is also the global
trend, he added.
</P>
<P>
The ATS was first introduced in November 1995 with the launch
of Rolling Forex, a currency futures contract. Since then all new
products have been introduced on the ATS.
</P>
<P>
Today a total of 30 futures and options contracts are traded
electronically. The Hang Seng Index futures and options,
introduced in 1986 and 1993 respectively, will migrate from their
current trading platform - open outcry - to that of the ATS in
1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
