<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia, PNG Ministerial Forum Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The 11th annual Australia and
Papua New Guinea (PNG) Ministerial Forum opened in Cairns in
northeast Australia Monday, with the Bougainville conflict, trade
arrangements, cross border security and customs matters high on
the agenda of the two-day talks.
</P>
<P>
At the opening meeting, PNG Foreign Minister Roy Yaki called on
the Australian government to be flexible in the application of aid
money in view of the depressed nature of the PNG economy, the
Australian Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a welcome from Australian Foreign Affairs
Minister Alexander Downer, Yaki said his government accepts the
need for greater accountability in the use of aid dollars, but
feels account must be taken of the combined effects on the PNG
economy of drought, depressed commodity prices and the Asian
currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said PNG was satisfied with the defense relationship between
the two countries, but there were matters of concern regarding the
settlement of the Bougainville conflict.
</P>
<P>
"While we agree with the new objectives of benchmarking and the
performance-driven nature of aid, we would ask Australia to take
due account of the depressed nature of the PNG economy," Yaki
said.
</P>
<P>
Downer said the bilateral relationship was back on track after
a period of uncertainty, and reaffirmed the importance of the
relationship to the Australian government.
</P>
<P>
He said resolution of the Bougainville conflict was high on the
agenda of the talks, pointing to the visits in the past week to
PNG by himself and Deputy Prime Minister Tim Fischer, and a
forthcoming visit by Defense Minister John Moore.
</P>
<P>
"Minister Moore will have talks with the Peace Monitoring Force
this week, and this and other ministerial visits are part of a
pattern of very useful exchanges," Downer said.
</P>
<P>
"There used to be a time when the personal relationship between
Australian and PNG ministers was very important," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking forward to a very constructive meeting on the
bilateral arrangements which the Australian government believes is
crucial." 
</P>
</TEXT>
