<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Savings Still Favored in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 21 (Xinhua) --Despite the People's Bank of
China cutting interest rates six times this year, the Chinese
still save over ten percent of their salaries in banks
each month, according to sources from the State Information Center.
</P>
<P>
This is higher than the average savings level for the Asian and
Pacific Region but it seems the Chinese people would like to save
more.
</P>
<P>
The Center was quoting the results of a survey released
recently by Master Card International, which examined savings and
consumer spending in the region overall.
</P>
<P>
It discovered that many Chinese residents are not satisfied
with their present savings level, comparing it unfavorably with
that of their Japanese neighbours.
</P>
<P>
However, after the People's Bank of China slashed interest
rates again recently financial observers reckon it will be hard to
tell if this will affect the levels of savings in the country.
</P>
<P>
The survey, which was first initiated in 1996, is carried out
in 13 countries and areas of the Asian and Pacific Region every
six months, with an admitted error rate of four percent. The
latest survey covered China's Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou
cities.
</P>
<P>
Most of those polled feel they do not save enough, and only 34
percent are satisfied with the amount they presently save.
</P>
<P>
Many people said that their savings are used for a wide range
of purposes such as the education of children, buying houses,
medical insurance and holidays.
</P>
<P>
Indeed, for many Chinese people buying houses has become one
of the main reasons for saving, thanks to the implementation of
housing reform policies in China over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
And 63 percent of Chinese respondents said they would spend the
money on their parents.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows, however, that few Chinese residents would
spend their savings on foreign holidays which are still considered
to be a luxury, afforded by only a small number of people.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Asian financial crisis has had a dramatic impact
on consumer spending habits in the Asian and Pacific Region. More
than 70 percent of those interviewed acknowledged that they are
now more careful in their spending because of the difficult
economic situation.
</P>
<P>
However, due to the limited impact of the crisis in China, only
47 percent of those polled in the three main cities said they had
became more careful over spending. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
