<HEADLINE> Newcastle Shareholders Reject Directors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 21 (Xinhua) -- A fiery annual meeting of
Newcastle United football club witnessed shareholders reject the
reinstatement of disgraced directors Freddie Shepherd and Douglas
Hall to the board on Monday.
</P>
<P>
A clear majority on the floor of the meeting opposed their
re-election in a show-of-hands vote forcing chief executive
Freddie Fletcher to call a formal poll of all shareholders.
</P>
<P>
However, with Shepherd and Hall themselves major
shareholders,this vote is expected to approve their re-elction.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, shareholders and fans were told that nothing will
happen regarding any proposed takeover until early next spring at
the soonest.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Newcastle admitted that it had struck a deal for a
potential sale of the club to US cable group NTL which
immediately took an initial 6.3% stake in the Magpies.
</P>
<P>
The meeting erupted a number of times with Fletcher forced to
repeatedly call for order as shareholders hurled abuse at the
podium. Several shareholders shouted "it's a stitch-up" over the
re-election issue.
</P>
<P>
The two disgraced directors who own a majority share of the
club were able to vote themselves back onto the board of the
football club earlier this month sparking the resignations of the
chairman and financial advisor.
</P>
<P>
The two had been forced out in July following their
disparaging remarks about Newcastle fans and leading player Alan
Shearer.
</P>
<P>
About 500 fans watched the latest meeting via a video link-up
to homeground St James' Park.
</P>
<P>
Long-time Newcastle supporter Ted Ablett, 70, said: "I have
supported this club since the 1940s and we need some stability
here.At present it is a shambles and I don't know what input we
can have this morning."
</P>
<P>
Shareholders of the stock exchange-listed Premier League club
are also expected to reject the proposed 160 million pounds
takeover by NTL.
</P>
<P>
An understanding leaves NTL, the UK's third largest
telecommunications and cable company, free to buy the rest of
Hall's shares and therefore a controlling stake in the club.
</P>
<P>
However, Fletcher told the meeting: "No offer has been made at
the moment and if one is, then full advice will be given to
shareholders at that time."
</P>
<P>
The cable group has said there would be no agreement on the
takeover bid until the Monopolies and Mergers Commission, the
UK's anti-competition watchdog, has approved of the takeover bid
of Manchester United by media group BSkyB. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
