<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Zone Enjoys Trade Surplus in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The euro zone enjoyed a trade
surplus of 5.2 billion ECU (6.24 billion U.S. dollars) in
September with the rest of the world, Eurostat reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Luxembourg-based statistical bureau of the European
community said that though the 11 euro countries enjoyed a
combined surplus, the surplus dropped 2.2 billion ECU (2.64
billion dollars) compared with the same month a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The European Union, however, fared even worse in September when
the 15-nation bloc sustained a trade deficit of 1.2 billion ECU
(1.44 billion dollars) with non-EU countries.
</P>
<P>
Twelve months ago, the European Union chalked up a surplus of
3.3 billion ECU (3.96 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The extra- and intra-trade growth continued to slow in
September for both the European Union and the euro zone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
