<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Turkey-Syria Disputes Abate, Not End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The Kurdish issue had long been
at the heart of the bitterness between Turkey and Syria, and this
October it flared up to push the two neighboring countries to the
brink of war.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to mediation efforts by regional countries and
self-restraint the two sides exercised, a weeks-long standoff
ended peacefully, sparing the conflict-stricken region of possibly
another catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's relations with Syria fared badly, primarily due to
alleged Damascus support to the Kurdish Workers' Party, a rebel
group outlawed in Turkey, Turkey's newly-founded alliance with
Israel, and the long-standing dispute over water resources.
</P>
<P>
Ankara threatened to resort to force if Damascus continues to
support the PKK, which has been fighting for autonomy in
southeastern Turkey. Some 37,000 people have been killed in the
14-year-old conflict.
</P>
<P>
Turkey intensified its pursuit of the guerrillas in and outside
its territory in recent years, hoping to root out the rebellion.
However, its military goal could not be fully attained because the
militants could always find shelter, as alleged, in Syria, Iraq
and Iran, who showed sympathy to the Kurdish movement.
</P>
<P>
At the parliament on October 1, Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel warned that his country reserved the right to respond
against Syria for Damascus' support to the PKK.
</P>
<P>
Then Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz said later that his government
might request a parliament consent for a war with Syria, although
war was not desired.
</P>
<P>
Turkey massed troops, tanks and artillery near Syria and
ordered fighter planes to take off from southern air bases and fly
at low-altitude along the common border, to substantiate its
threat.
</P>
<P>
This was when Egypt and Iran came to the rescue. Together with
other Arab states, they urged for reason, self-restraint, and a
peaceful approach to sort out the differences. Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak shuttled between Ankara and Damascus in early
October and Iran sent its Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi to talk
the two sides into a dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The mediation worked. High-ranking officials from Turkey and
Syria held crucial talks on October 19-20 in the southern Turkish
city of Ceyhan not far from the Syrian border, and cut a deal.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement reached, Syria pledged to shut down PKK
camps on its territory and in the Syrian-controlled Bekka valley
in Lebanon, and to prevent PKK militants from launching
cross-border attacks on Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkey also achieved what it wished for: to dislodge PKK leader
Abdullah Ocalan out of Syria, and possibly this region.
</P>
<P>
Despite the peaceful solution to this row, Turkey's rift with
Syria and other countries in the region, who resented Ankara's
growingly close ties with Israel, seemed to be widening.
</P>
<P>
Syria, located between Turkey and Israel, said Turkish-Israeli
military alliance is targeted against the Arab world, especially
itself. It accused the predominantly Muslim, but politically
secular neighbor of betraying the interests of the Muslims.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two years, Turkey and Israel signed a couple of
military training and defense industry cooperation accords, much
to the rancor and animosity of its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Most Arab countries in the region still regarded Israel as a
threat to their peace and security, particularly at a time when
the Middle East peace process was stalled because of what they
called Israeli intransigence.
</P>
<P>
They feared that closer Turkish-Israeli military alliance would
further tip the balance of power in the region greatly in Israel's
favor.
</P>
<P>
Turkey argued that their relationship was of totally bilateral
nature and not directed at any third country, blaming Syria for
inciting the Arab world to confront Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the lingering problem of water sharing is
re-surfacing. The Euphrates and Tigris rivers both originate in
the mountains of Turkey and run down through Syria and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
For years, Syria and Iraq have complained Turkey did not allow
more water to flow downstream; now Syria is accusing Ankara of
building more dams on the Euphrates that would further jeopardize
its water supply.
</P>
<P>
In the past, late Turkish President Turgut Ozal had threatened
to use water as a kind of "weapon" to force Syria to withdraw
support for the Kurds by "restricting the water flow" to Syria.
</P>
<P>
Now that the Kurdish issue is resolved, at least for now, will
the "weapon" itself become a next flash point between the two
neighbors in the future? It's anybody's guess. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
