<HEADLINE> 12 Foreign Firms Engage in Mining in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has attracted 12
foreign firms to engage in its mining sector since the country
enacted the New Mining Law in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The firms from Australia, Canada, Japan, Malaysia, Singapore,
Thailand and the United States are engaged in prospecting and
exploration of mineral resources such as gold and copper.
</P>
<P>
The firms have signed agreements with Myanmar on mineral
prospecting and exploration, and eight of them have formed joint
ventures with enterprises under the Myanmar Ministry of Mines.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar Ivanhoe Copper Co. Ltd. between Myanmar and Canada
is one of such joint ventures, which produces cathode copper from
Sabai Taung and Kyay Sin Taung mines.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, plans are underway to develop the Let Pan Taung
copper mine and upon completion, the copper mine will become one
of the largest mine of its kind in the area.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, foreign investment in
Myanmar's mining sector amounted to 501.36 million U.S. dollars in
43 related projects at the end of May this year.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics also show that the output value of
Myanmar's mining sector rose 1.5 percent in the 1997-98 fiscal
year which ended in March as compared with the previous year.
</P>
</TEXT>
