<HEADLINE> HK Sports Chief Praises "Behind-the-Scenes Hero" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 21 (Xinhua) -- While praising the success
obtained by athletes of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR) at the 13th Asian Games in Bangkok, the head of the
Amateur Sports Federation and Olympic Committee of Hong Kong, Chi
na, reminded people here on Monday not to forget those behind the
successful athletes.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a ceremony held at the Hong Kong International
Airport to welcome the return of the Hong Kong SAR delegation
from the Bangkok Games, Timothy Fok said that the greatest glory
should be given to the triumphant SAR athletes, who had made
painstaking efforts for achieving their goals at the December
6-20 Games.
</P>
<P>
For example, Nanquan (Southern Boxing) champion Ng Siu Ching
had trained in Beijing for three months for her title-winning
Wushu performance of just one minute and 20 seconds in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
Fok also noted the fruitful efforts by Shen Jinkang, coach of
Hong Kong SAR cyclist Wong Kam Po, who won the men's
200-kilometer individual road race in Bangkok. Shen, a former
head coach of China's national cycling team, has been the head
coach of Hong Kong cyclists since 1994. Finishing fourth at the
road race in the Hiroshima Asian Games the same year, Wong
gradually took Asia's top spot under the instruction of the
former Chinese national coach.
</P>
<P>
Fok also promised to make efforts in trying to have
post-career arrangements made for retired athletes, which was a
focal point raised by many of Hong Kong SAR's Asian Games medal
winners.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's first ever Asian Games gold medal came when Che
Kok Hom took the women's blowing title at the Seoul Games in
1986. Olympic champion windsurfer Lee Lai Shan took for Hong
Kong its second Asian Games title 12 years later, this time in
Bangkok, where SAR athletes competed for the time under the name
of Hong Kong, China.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong SAR athletes grabbed five gold, six silver and six
bronze medals at Bangkok, which represented the best ever
performance by any Hong Kong delegations at Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
The SAR Government had planned to hold celebrations on
Wednesday, including open bus ride by Asian Games medal winners
and song and dance performance by local artists at a square in
eastern Tsim Sha Tsui. The Hong Kong Sports Development Board
had set cash prizes for the medal winners at the Bangkok Games,
with gold medal winners each to take 500,000 HK dollars (64,100
U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
