<HEADLINE> Nigeria, Mali to Set up Joint Trade Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria and Mali have agreed to
form a high joint commission to boost commercial activities and
promote cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued at the end of a visit to Mali Saturday by
Nigerian Head of State General Abdulsalami Abubakar said that a
constitutive session of the commission would be held at the
earliest possible time, New Nigerian newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
General Abubakar and President Omar Alpha Konare of Mali
agreed to intensify periodical sectorial meetings at all levels
in order to promote mutual cooperation between the people of
Nigeria and Mali.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders reaffirmed their commitment to the objectives
and principles of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS), saying that an effective bilateral and regional
cooperation among the ECOWAS member states is a necessary
prerequisite for regional economic integration.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria and Mali, both are ECOWAS members, are committed to
the use of dialogue and consultation in resolving conflicts and
to the maintenance of peace and security in the sub-region, the
communique said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders reiterated their support to the ECOWAS peace
plan on Guinea Bissau, the restoration of peace in Liberia and
the constitutional government in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
On other continental issues, they regretted the persistence of
hot beds in the Great Lakes region, Angola, Guinea Bissau, Sierra
Leone and the Comoros.
</P>
<P>
They called on member states of the Organization of African
Unity to take necessary measures to ensure effective economic
cooperation among African countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
