<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Desert Fox" Action Dismissed By Chinese Military Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese military experts have
dismissed the U.S. and British four day action against Iraq as a
"Much Ado About Nothing" scenario, to quote the famous British
playwright William Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and British governments insist that the operation known
as 'Desert Fox' achieved what they wanted.
</P>
<P>
However, Chen Bojiang, a research fellow at the Chinese Academy of
Military Science, points out that the U.S. and British governments
made it clear that one of the major objectives of the action was
to overthrow Saddam Hussein's regime.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously Saddam's throne has not been threatened and any
anti-government action in Iraq is still in its infancy," added
Chen.
</P>
<P>
Another objective was to destroy Iraq's facilities for
producing weapons of mass destruction and the long-range cruise
missiles launched to demolish his installations outnumbered those
in the Gulf War seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
"However, the percentage of accurate hits was quite limited
according to an assessment by even both sides," points out Zhang
Yuliang, a professor at the Chinese Institute of National Defense.
</P>
<P>
Indeed, he said that the real, and hidden, agenda of the
U.S. and British governments is to take control of oil resources
in the Middle East in order to maintain their strategic advantage
in the region.
</P>
<P>
However, after the action, the two governments have faced severe
criticism and denunciation from both their adversaries and even
their friends. More important for the future, is the potential
threat of the wrath of the whole Muslim world in view of the
proximity to the holy term of Ramadan before the attacks
commenced, and which largely contributed to a relatively quick
ending of the engagement.
</P>
<P>
The two Chinese experts also believe that the Operation "Desert
Fox" has undeniable connections with U.S. President Bill Clinton's
personal domestic embarrassment. Despite the seriousness of the
military action in terms of international relations, and the
temporary postponement of a vote for impeachment due to the sudden
and surprise attacks on Iraq, the U.S. House of Representatives
still voted to pass two articles calling for Clinton's impeachment
during the same week of the attacks.
</P>
<P>
It is suggested that Clinton's hope of "killing two birds with
one stone" finally ended in disillusionment on both counts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali King Accepts PM's Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Nepali King Birendra
accepted Monday evening the resignation tendered by Prime Minister
Girija Prasad Koirala, Radio Nepal said.
</P>
<P>
The king asked the present government to continue its function
until a new government is formed, the state-run radio said,
quoting a notice issued by the king's Principal Press Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
He also asked any member of the Lower House who can garner a
majority of 103 seats to stake claim to power by Wednesday
evening, another notice issued by the secretariat said.
</P>
<P>
When Koirala tendered his resignation earlier Monday, he also
submitted to the king a letter bearing the signatures of
legislators from three parties supporting his premiership in the
coalition government to be formed.
</P>
<P>
It was not clear how many legislators had signed the letter,
but the three parties -- the ruling Nepali Congress (NC), the main
opposition Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxism-Leninism,
CPN-UML) and the Nepal Sadbhavana Party -- have a majority of 140
seats in the house, much more than needed to form a new coalition.
</P>
<P>
Koirala resigned in accordance with a decision of the NC
Central Working Committee and an agreement the NC reached Sunday
with the CPN-UML.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-UML agreed to support the efforts of the NC in forming
a new coalition government to conduct general elections in April
1999.
</P>
<P>
The two parties agreed to include all the political parties
represented in parliament into the new government to be headed by
Koirala.
</P>
<P>
The latest round of political turmoil erupted when the
Communist Party of Nepal (Marxism-Leninism, CPN-ML) quit the
coalition government on December 10 after sharing power with the
NC for three and a half months.
</P>
<P>
The party alleged that the NC had failed to implement the
agreements reached with it and other left parties in August.
</P>
<P>
It registered a no-confidence motion on Sunday against the NC
government with the support of other parties.
</P>
<P>
King Birendra had decided to call a special session of
parliament on Thursday to discuss the motion, which becomes
meaningless with the resignation of Prime Minister Koirala.
</P>
<P>
Koirala's government is the fifth in the country since the
mid-term polls in November 1994 which produced a hung parliament
with no single party holding a majority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
