<HEADLINE> Fighting in Angola's Kuito City Dies Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The fighting in Kuito City,
provincial capital of Angola's central Bie Province has died
down, the government-run Journal of Angola newspaper reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kuito has been the center where the most fierce fighting took
place since mid November between the government troops and the
forces of the opposition National Union for Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, UNITA President Jonas Savimbi's troops
stopped bombarding and only sporadic shootings were heard after
the government forces launched a counter attack against the
rebels surrounding the city.
</P>
<P>
The reinforced government troops launched massive attacks on
the town of Cruzeiro, 35 kilometers south of Kuito, releasing the
pressure upon the defenders.
</P>
<P>
However, the paper acknowledged that it is still too early to
say that Kuito has been rescued from the siege by the UNITA
troops since the routes linking the city with the outside world
are still controlled by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
UNITA reinforcements are reported to have massed toward Kuito,
apparently preparing to mount new attacks on the city.
</P>
<P>
There have been big-scale conflicts again between the
government army and the UNITA forces in the central provinces of
Huambo and Bie in the past month and more.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government accused the UNITA of launching attacks
first by using tanks, armored vehicles, long-range artillery and
surface-to-air missiles.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA has got the upper hand by occupying most parts of
the two provinces of Huambo and Bie and the Angolan government
army has to retreat so as to defend the capital cities of the two
provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
