<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Remain Tough On Crimes, Senior Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 21 (Xinhua) -- China is determined to
maintain its high profile campaign of safeguarding social and
political stability through into 1999.
</P>
<P>
Public security departments will be urged to strike hard
against criminals, according to Luo Gan, secretary of the Central
Political Science and Law Committee, who made his remarks at a
national conference on political science and law in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
He said that with China next year celebrating the 50th
anniversary of the founding of the country, and resuming its right
to exercise sovereignty over Macao, it will be a specially
important period in the country's history and development.
</P>
<P>
"We must crack down on crimes that threaten national security,
strike hard against serious economic crimes to protect national
economic safety ... and do everything to maintain stability in
rural areas," said Luo who is also a member of the Political
Bureau and the Secretariat of the CPC Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
He called for the building up of a strong and highly qualified
force of legal practitioners and cautioned delegates not to
overestimate the progress achieved during the rectification and
educational campaign conducted throughout this year.
</P>
<P>
As well as summing up the past year's achievements, the
conference is expected to outline pubic security tasks and
responsibilities for 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
