<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Israel's Economic Recession Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Despite various stimulation
measures taken by the government, Israel's economy is expected to
rise by only 1.6 percent in 1998, the lowest in the decade due to
an emerging global economic shrink and a restrictive monetary
policy introduced more than two years ago.
</P>
<P>
The figure, given by Israeli Finance ministry in its latest
report, is based on the country's GDP growth rates in the past
three quarters, namely 1.4 percent in the third quarter, 1.6
percent in the second quarter and 2 percent in the first three
months.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's data also pointed to a remarkable fall in public
consumption and a substantial decline in investments in 1998.
</P>
<P>
From the second quarter to the third quarter of the year,
investments in fixed assets (excluding ships and aircraft) shrank
by 19.4 percent, spending on residential buildings by 13.5 percent
and expenditure in the other sectors by 21.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, the country's per capita consumption,
which is a measure of the individual's living standard, shrank 1
percent. It is the fifth consecutive quarterly decline since last
year, the highest in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, there seems to be few likelihood that the government
meets its target of a 3 percent rise in the state income from
taxes and fees in 1998. Till November, the state income increased
only by 1.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown of Israeli economic growth began in the second
half of 1996 after the Likud government came to power and took a
restrictive monetary policy in order to cool down the then
overheated and inflationary economy.
</P>
<P>
From 1990 to 1995, Israel's annual GDP growth rate was
approximately 6 percent. In comparison, the GDP growth rates in
1996 and 1997 were 4.7 percent and 2.2 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
In addition, local analysts said, the instability of world
financial markets, an abrupt decline in global economic growth and
a sharp reduction in the flow of capital to the developing
countries, have contributed to the downturn in the Israeli
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The government said the country's economic growth was also
hampered by a decreasing number of immigrants to Israel since 1996
and constant terrorism activities in the region as a result of
stagnancy in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The decrease of immigrants led to a halt in the growth of
consumption of durable goods and investment in residential
buildings, while the stagnancy in the peace process raised
economic uncertainty and had an immediate effect on tourism.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the contraction of international trade this year
has led to the recession of Israel's export. The country's export
of goods and services increased by 7.2 percent in 1997, but in
1998 is expected to rise by 3.1 percent only, the lowest growth
rate in the last 15 years.
</P>
<P>
And the country's transition from traditional industries to
high-tech industries has also had a short-term downward effect on
the export growth. The high-tech industries grew rapidly in 1998,
which accounts for more than 30 percent of total export till
now. But the growth in this sector failed to offset the downturn
in export in such sectors as textiles, where the competition from
cheap-labor countries has caused the closure of many Israeli
plants.
</P>
<P>
Israel's local currency shekel has depreciated more than 20
percent against the U.S. dollar in the first 11 months this
year. The devaluation makes the government hard to meet the
target of reducing the inflation rate to 4 percent this year and
the next year.
</P>
<P>
The economic growth slowdown in Israel is likely to cause the
unemployment rate to hit a new high of 8.8 percent in 1998
compared with 7.7 percent in 1997 and 6.7 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In order to get the economy back on a path of high growth, the
Likud government in 1998 continued its economic reforms, including
abolition of foreign-currency restrictions and reduction of its
direct involvement in the economic activities and acceleration of
the privatization of the government corporations.
</P>
<P>
In April 1998, the Finance Ministry announced the lifting of
most of foreign-currency restrictions on Israeli residents and
business sectors in an effort to encourage more foreign investment
in the country's economy and intensify competition in the
financial services.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government succeeded in the late September to
sell 15 percent shares of the state-owned Bank Leumi, Israel's
second largest financial institution, to a variety of local and
foreign investors on the London and Zurich stock exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry said the government's privatization
program in 1998 is surely to make the state-owned enterprises more
efficient, and encourage the Israeli economy to become more
involved in international business.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government has decided to increase investment in
infrastructure by almost 240 million dollars next year in a bid to
boost economic growth and employment. It also plans to allocate 24
million dollars in 1999 to help 30,000 unemployed workers take
part in retraining lessons and get new jobs.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said if the economic reforms proceed smoothly in
the country, Israel's economic growth rate is expected to increase
moderately to 2.2-2.5 percent in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
