<HEADLINE> One of China's Greatest Scholars Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 21 (Xinhua) -- There was a quiet cremation
here today for Qian Zhongshu who passed away two days ago, and who
is regarded by many as one of China's greatest writers and
scholars of this century.
</P>
<P>
A graduate of Qinghua University and Britain's Oxford
University, the 88-year old intellectual was known for his efforts
to interweave Western and Eastern cultures.
</P>
<P>
His most famous novel "The Besieged City", depicts the ideas,
hopes and aspirations of Chinese intellectuals. He was also
respected for his collections of literary critiques. During the
chaotic "Cultural Revolution" (1966-76), he was one of the most
well-known intellectuals who were persecuted.
</P>
<P>
At his own request, the funeral ceremony was very simple
without any music and his body was carried in a mini-bus to the
Babaoshan Cemetery for Revolutionaries in Beijing accompanied by
his 87 year old widow Yang Jiang.
</P>
<P>
Present at the ceremony were only twenty other mourners,
including Li Tieying, a member of the political bureau of the
Chinese Communist Party Central Committee and president of the
Chinese Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Yang placed a small basket of flowers on her husband's body
before it was cremated. In accordance with his will, his ashes
will not be preserved and none of his friends or students had been
invited to the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The couple were highly regarded in China for their wisdom,
commitment to each other, humility and disregard for wealth.
</P>
<P>
Last night Yang received a telephone message of condolence
from Chinese president Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
Many of Qian's contemporaries believe that he was truly
representative of the times.
</P>
<P>
One of his grieving colleagues admitted that if the funeral had
been public probably thousands of people might have attended to
pay their last respects to the man many considered a master.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
