<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People's Bank of China Gets Tough on Ownership Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China
(PBOC) today issued a circular demanding state-owned medium-sized
and small enterprises and collectively-owned firms to closely
monitor and administer creditor's rights when undergoing ownership
transformation.
</P>
<P>
It stated that this is to standardize the ownership
transformation of enterprises and prevent financial risks.
</P>
<P>
The protection of financial claims is crucial to preventing
financial risks and promoting economic and financial development
and social stability, the bank stressed.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that there have been cases in which some
enterprises have tried to evade paying off their bank debt during
the process of their restructuring, but in fact this practice only
harmed their credit rating with banks.
</P>
<P>
Relevant departments have been instructed to improve their
responsibility, and realize the importance of protecting financial
claims. They have also been told to correctly handle the
administration of enterprise transformation while ensuring the
protection of financial claims.
</P>
<P>
The bank has asked departments in charge of enterprise
transformation to carefully study and examine enterprise
transformation plans and closely supervise their
implementation. Enterprises undergoing ownership transformation
must solve issues related to financial claims according to
existing laws and policies, while financial institutions, as major
creditors, must be invited to participate in the changeover.
</P>
<P>
The bank's circular highlights and details just what
constitutes enterprise ownership transformation: share-holding
restructuring, mergers, auctions and transference of assets,
leasing and contracting, joint-venture restructuring and
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
The bank has also insisted that all fiscal, taxation and
industrial and commercial administration departments strengthen
their supervision on the procedures of enterprise transformation,
in a bid to stop losses of state-owed assets and taxes. It calls
for severe punishments for enterprises which have evaded their
financial responsibilities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-Ender: Angolan Peace Process Faltering Into </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The rumbling of gunfire has
shattered the hope of the implementation of Angolan peace
process, which should have been concluded this year in the
southern African country.
</P>
<P>
Since early December, fierce fighting in central Angola
between the government forces and the rebel troops of the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) has
resulted in the death of hundreds of people, while some 100,000
people have been forced to flee their homes.
</P>
<P>
As heavy weapons like tanks, long-range artillery and
surface-to-air missiles were used in the battles, Angolan Foreign
Minister Venancio da Silva Moura said last week that "the Angolan
peace process is at a crucial point and a full-scale civil war
may break out at any moment."
</P>
<P>
This is, no doubt, a failure to comply with the Lusaka
Protocol which aims at a lasting peace in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The Lusaka peace accord signed in the Zambian capital in 1994
is a landmark which has ended two decades of civil war between
the government and UNITA and unfolded a new initiative for peace
efforts.
</P>
<P>
Three years after the agreement, a unified armed force and a
government of national unity and reconciliation have been formed,
with UNITA members formally sworn in in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
However, at the critical point of the Lusaka Protocol, UNITA
was reluctant to fully demobilize its army and refused to hand
over several key areas it occupies to the government as
prescribed in the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that the move indicates Jonas Savimbi,
Chairman of UNITA, and his supporters would not let go of the
"assets" they accumulated over the past 30 years. Moreover, the
protracted civil war has deprived the two sides of any trust of
each other. Now that the People's Liberation Movement of Angola
takes the state power in its hand, the UNITA could hardly imagine
assuming the role of "political opposition" under the roof of its
long-time foe.
</P>
<P>
Hence the peace process ran into a stalemate, with domestic
conflicts escalating and frequent maneuver of UNITA military
forces in an attempt to attack government controlled cities,
bringing the country to the fringes of crisis.
</P>
<P>
The death of U.N. special envoy to Angola, Alioune Blondin
Beye, in a plane accident forced the mediation work which Beye
had been so competent with to a virtual standstill. The Angolan
government, in despair, decided to deal a strong blow to Savimbi
who it believes is determined to wage an "armed struggle for
state power."
</P>
<P>
On September 1, the government announced the suspension of
UNITA members' positions in the government of national unity and
reconciliation as well as the parliament, forcing most of them to
express their willingness to stick to the peace process and
desert Savimbi by forming a splinter UNITA Renovation Committee.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government accused Savimbi of being "a war
criminal" and broke up all its contacts with the former rebel
movement. Instead, it recognized the UNITA Renovation Committee
as the only legitimate dialogist over the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The move, by causing division inside the opposition UNITA and
assuming the legality to "wipe out the armed bandits of Savimbi"
actually kills two birds with one stone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-Ender: Angolan Peace Process Faltering Into </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, the move was not agreed to by the United Nations
mediators, who believe that despite the obstacles set up by
Savimbi to the peace process, Savimbi should be allowed one more
chance given the fact that he is one of the two signatories of
the Lusaka Protocol.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Security Council in October, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said there had been "some negative
changes" recently in the Angolan situation, which "pose serious
threats to further advancing the peace process."
</P>
<P>
The words aroused strong complaints from the Angolan
government. Angolan President Eduardo dos Santos said in his
letter to Annan that "it has been proved by history many times
that Savimbi will not give up his war policy," and that Angolan
people are determined to "completely cast him aside" and
accomplish the rest of the tasks prescribed in the Lusaka peace
agreement together with the "patriotic UNITA Renovation
Committee."
</P>
<P>
The differences between Angolan government and the United
Nations worsened the situation in the peace process. U.N. new
envoy to Angola Issa Diallo could hardly start working since he
took office in late August.
</P>
<P>
Neither has the joint committee which consists of U.N., the
Angolan government, UNITA and the troika observer countries --
Portugal, Russia and the United States -- opened any session
since.
</P>
<P>
With escalating domestic conflicts, the government army
launched attacks at UNITA occupied areas in central Angola in
mid-November, and besieged Bailundo and Andulo, where UNITA
headquarters are located.
</P>
<P>
UNITA, on the other hand, held about 15 U.N. peacekeepers as
virtual hostages. There were reports that UNITA had withdrawn
its main force to forest areas in the east, getting prepared for
long-time war with the backup of diamond resources in the Lunda
provinces.
</P>
<P>
To rid the war-torn country of deteriorating crisis, serious
negotiations were then held between the U.N. representative and
the Angolan government.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council approved a resolution on December 3,
citing the failure to implement Lusaka peace accord by the UNITA
leadership as the main cause for the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The resolution asked UNITA to demobilize its army
unconditionally and withdraw its forces from areas it took over
from the government.
</P>
<P>
It also urged UNITA to cooperate with the government
completely in a bid to promote the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council also renewed the mandate of its
peacekeepers in Angola for another three months in an effort to
prevent a return to war in the southern African nation.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government expressed its "satisfaction" toward the
resolution. However, it is still far from a compromised stand
accepted by both sides.
</P>
<P>
The recent armed clashes in central Angola which witnessed
dozens of tanks and long-range cannons on the UNITA side had been
reportedly a great setback to the government army.
</P>
<P>
According to local press reports that UNITA's Chairman Jonas
Savimbi, who was planning to announce victory on December 25, the
founding day of his party, had to start his action on December 1,
after the government became aware of UNITA's conspiracy and made
response to it.
</P>
<P>
The government and UNITA troops are now engaging in fierce
fightings in the central part of the country, where UNITA men
have taken control of a big part of Huambo and Bie provinces,
while the government forces have withdrawn to Huambo and Kuito,
capital cities of the two provinces after suffering heavy losses.
</P>
<P>
All signs indicate that the two sides are really in for it,
and therefore, currently there seems to be no end in sight to the
Angolan peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
