<HEADLINE> Australian Govt Urged to Protect Rice Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Australia's New South Wales
Premier Bob Carr Monday called on the federal government to
protect the Australian rice industry against a Japanese decision
to impose huge tariffs on imported foreign rice.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday the Japanese government announced a 1,200-percent
tariff on foreign rice, which will impact heavily on Australia's
390-million-U.S.-dollar rice industry, Carr said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Apart from a small quantity grown in Victoria, New South Wales
produces most of Australia's rice in the Murray and Murrumbidgee
areas. In recent years Australian rice has made inroads into the
Japanese market with new rice strains such as Japonica and
Koshihikari developed specifically for that market.
</P>
<P>
Carr said he had written to Deputy Prime Minister and Minister
for Trade Tim Fischer to ask him to "do everything in his power"
to protect the Australian rice industry.
</P>
<P>
"I strongly urge the deputy prime minister to make the
strongest representations to the Japanese... they must not
proceed with plans to impose a tariff on imported rice," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said Tim Fischer had already contacted with the
U.S. trade representative talking about a joint action against
Japanese tariffs. 
</P>
