<HEADLINE> Angola Threatens to Break Deals with De Beers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Angola has threatened to
cancel all agreements with diamond giant De Beers if it proves
the South African company is involved in business with the
National Union for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
The Southern African Broadcasting Association reported Monday
that Angola issued the warning following allegations of such ties
by the British human rights group Global Witness.
</P>
<P>
Jose Dias, administrator of the Angolan National Diamonds
Company, was quoted as saying that the government of Angolan
President Jose Dos Santos would investigate the charges by the
London-based group.
</P>
<P>
He said that Angola would scrap some agreements with De Beers
if it confirmed that the multinational company and the UNITA were
involved in deals.
</P>
<P>
In its report, Global Witness accused De Beers of carrying out
business, worth at least three billion U.S. Dollars with the
UNITA since the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The human rights group claimed that De Beers was involved in
many mining projects, mostly in eastern Angola which had been
controlled by the UNITA, the country's leading opposition party.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA, which is under United Nations sanctions, has
renewed the civil war, violating a peace accord it signed with
the Angolan government in 1994 in Zambian capital Lusaka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
