<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jurist Calls for Efforts to Punish Subversive Activities (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, December 21 (Xinhua) -- A prominent jurist said today
that all subversive activities endangering China's socialist
system and state security should be punished in accordance with
law.
</P>
<P>
"The most important legal basis for a trial of subversion is
the Constitution of the People's Republic of China," said Ma
Kechang, a professor at the Law School of Wuhan University in
central China.
</P>
<P>
According to the Constitution, China is a socialist country
with a people's democratic dictatorship led by the working class
and based on the alliance of workers and peasants, and socialism
is its fundamental system, Ma said.
</P>
<P>
Ma noted that in accordance with the country's Criminal Law,
activities subverting state power and attempting to overturn the
socialist system are actions endangering state security. And
therefore, "any of these activities should be punished according
to law", he said.
</P>
<P>
Subversive activities encompass enticing and contacting people
to overthrow the state power, or even planning to establish a
"society" or "party", he said, adding that plotting or carrying
out such activities are also considered to be subversion.
</P>
<P>
"Any such activities that are carried out constitutes an
accomplished offense," Ma said. Subjectively, subversion of the
state power or overturning socialism is on purpose, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to Ma, major subversion criminals may be sentenced to
imprisonment of 10 years or more, or even given a life sentence;
but those who are not actively participating in subversive
activities may receive a sentence of less than three years.
</P>
<P>
Ma said that according to the Constitution, people's courts in
China have the right to conduct trials independently, without any
interference from administrations, organizations or individuals.
</P>
<P>
"China's courts at different levels try criminal cases on their
own, including cases of subversion, without the interference of
government," Ma stressed.
</P>
<P>
Ma has been engaged in the study of Eastern and Western law
codes for 50 years, and took part in drafting and revising
China's criminal law, including the new one adopted a year ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jurist Calls for Efforts to Punish Subversive Activities (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to Ma, it is common practice in most countries of the
world to investigate the criminal responsibility of anyone accused
of subversive activities, which are generally regarded as serious
crimes.
</P>
<P>
In this respect, he said, the criminal laws of Germany, France,
Italy, Austria and several other countries all have stipulations
rather similar to those of China, and the penalties for the crime
of subversion are fairly severe.
</P>
<P>
For example, he said, the Criminal Law of France which came
into effect in 1994 stipulates that anyone conducting one or more
activities harmful to the system of the republic or the
territorial integrity of the state can be convicted of treason,
which can lead to a 30-year imprisonment and a fine of three
million francs.
</P>
<P>
The professor went on to say that some Western media have
misinterpreted China's criminal trials, attempting to say that in
China the subverting of state power is the same as "regarding
democracy as a crime".
</P>
<P>
"This misinterpretation derives not only from their lack of
knowledge about the criminals' concrete activities, but also from
their misunderstanding of China's laws," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that China is a socialist country exercising a people's
democratic dictatorship, and that people's democracy has become an
inalienable part of China's social system.
</P>
<P>
"China's laws grant the people a wide range of democratic
rights, but democracy cannot go beyond the Constitution, let alone
become an excuse for attempts to subvert state power and overthrow
the existing social system," he stressed. "It's the same situation
even in those developed capitalist countries." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strategist on Global Security Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The global security
situation this year has exhibited three characteristics, namely,
continuing crises, greater inclination toward foreign military
interference, and strong challenges to security agencies across
the world.
</P>
<P>
Xiong Guangkai, Director of the China Institute for
International Strategic Studies (CIISS), made the comments at a
CIISS annual metting here today.
</P>
<P>
Xiong, also deputy chief of general staff of the Chinese
People's Liberation Army, described the year 1998 as an
extraordinary year filled with security crises.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the number of security crises and armed
conflicts around the globe has averaged around 10 a year since
the end of the Cold War, far exceeding the average of 4
during the period of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out, political and diplomatic approaches
remain a major trend in solving international disputes, citing as
one example the peaceful resolution of Peru-Ecuadorian border
issues which had been suspended for over a century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
