<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Clarifies Confusion on Medical Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Board of
Investment (BOI) said Monday it has given approval for the
setting-up of a training institute affiliated to a foreign medical
school but not an international medical college.
</P>
<P>
BOI Chairman Thilan Wijesinghe made the clarification in a
statement issued Monday afternoon in response to confused media
reports about the proposed project and protests by local medical
students against establishing an international medical college in
Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Wijesinghe, who is also director general of the BOI, said in
the statement that the approval granted by the BOI is for the
setting-up of a training institute affiliated to a foreign medical
school but not an international medical college.
</P>
<P>
Media reports earlier this month said that Sri Lanka will set
up an international medical college in Colombo with an in-house
teaching hospital, the first of its kind in the country.
</P>
<P>
The reports also said students passing the college will be
awarded degrees by the world renowned Aberdeen University in the
United Kingdom with which the college is tied up.
</P>
<P>
The reports evoked controversy in medical circles and
demonstrations by medical students who worry about their future
competition.
</P>
<P>
Wijesinghe said it should be emphasized that the proposed
training institution will not grant medical degrees locally as
this is explicitly prohibited under the University Act.
</P>
<P>
He noted the proposed facility is in no way similar to the
North Colombo Medical Campus which has conferred local degrees for
many years.
</P>
<P>
Doctors obtaining degrees through the foreign university
affiliated to this institution will be able to practice in Sri
Lanka only if they sit for routine exams and abide by any other
conditions imposed by the relevant ministry, Wijesinghe added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
