<HEADLINE> China's Iron, Steel Output Grows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 21 (Xinhua) -- China produced 104 million
tons of steel in the first 11 months of 1998, up 6.5 percent
from the same period last year, and the output of rolled steel
hit 94 million tons, up 9.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures from the State Administration of
Metallurgical Industry also indicate that although the sector
realized a gross industrial output value of 160.9 billion yuan
during the period, its profit stood at only 443 million yuan, down
61.97 percent from the corresponding 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
A research report from the Administration attributes the drop
in profit to an increase in transportation and electricity costs
as well as price reductions for rolled steel.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the price reduction for rolled steel
is due to the increase of domestic output, and rising imports of
these products from Japan, Russia and the Republic of Korea at a
considerably lower prices. 
</P>
