<HEADLINE> Nepali PM Resigns for Formation of New Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Girija
Prasad Koirala Monday tendered his resignation to King Birendra to
make way for the formation of a new coalition government to
conduct general elections.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Nepali Congress (NC) said in a press statement that
the move was taken in accordance with the decision of its Central
Working Committee and the agreement reached Sunday with the main
opposition Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxism-Leninism,
CPN-UML).
</P>
<P>
Koirala also submitted to the king a letter with signatures of
legislators from the NC, the CPN-UML and the Nepal Sadbhavana
Party (NSP) supporting his continued premiership in the new
coalition, the NC said.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-UML agreed Sunday to support the efforts of the ruling
Nepali Congress (NC) to form a new coalition government for
conducting the elections in April 1999.
</P>
<P>
The NC and the CPN-UML also agreed to include the two factions
of the National Democratic Party (RPP), the NSP and the Communist
Party of Nepal (Marxism-Leninism, CPN-ML) into the new cabinet,
which will be small in size.
</P>
<P>
But the CPN-ML, which quit the coalition with the NC on
December 10, registered a no-confidence motion Sunday against the
NC government together with the RPP and the Nepal Workers and
Peasants Party.
</P>
<P>
King Birendra had decided to call a special session of
parliament Thursday as requested by the CPN-ML and its supporters
to discuss the no-confidence motion, which becomes meaningless
with the resignation of Prime Minister Koirala.
</P>
<P>
CPN-ML General Secretary Bam Dev Gautam said Sunday that there
was no chance of a coalition between his party and the NC under
Koirala's premiership again.
</P>
<P>
The party pulled out of the government after sharing power with
the NC for three and a half months. It alleged that the NC had
failed to implement the agreements reached with it and other left
parties in August.
</P>
<P>
The Himalayan kingdom has witnessed five governments since the
mid-term polls in November 1994 which produced a hung parliament
where no single party holds a majority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
