<HEADLINE> China's Overseas Tourism Growing Steadily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 21 (Xinhua) -- China's overseas tourism
industry has not been influenced by the Asian financial crisis and
this summer's flooding, as the number of overseas tourists grew by
10.93 percent in the first ten months this year over the same 1997
period.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest statistics from the China National
Tourism Administration (CNTA), the country hosted 52.16 million
overseas tourists in the January-October period, with earnings
from tourism rising 2.95 percent to 10.3 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The number of foreign tourists decreased 5.06 percent to 5.91
million, while the number of tourists from Hong Kong and Macao
grew 13.9 percent to 44.33 million.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong Province and Beijing and Shanghai Municipalities were
the three largest tourist magnets, and Japan, Russia, and the
United States were the three largest tourist sources.
</P>
<P>
The CNTA is now preparing for the 1999 World Horticulture
Exposition to be held in Kunming, capital of southwest China's
Yunnan Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
