<HEADLINE> Myanmar Eases Ban on Certain Products to Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has agreed to lift a
ban on the export of wood and fishery products to Thailand, but
will continue to impose import restrictions on consumer goods from
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Thai Commerce Ministry sources on Monday confirmed media
reports that Myanmar made the decision following a request from
Thailand a month ago to relax export and import restrictions in a
bid to increase trade.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has banned the export of 31 types of products,
including the much-needed cattle, gems and coal, to Thailand in an
effort to reverse a trade imbalance. It also bans import of
certain consumer and luxury items including monosodium glutamate,
soft drinks, biscuits, canned fruit and vegetables, fresh fruit,
instant noodles, liquor and cigarettes from Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Commerce Minister Pravich Rattanapian repeated the Thai
request when he met his Myanmar counterpart Myo Tint in Rangoon
earlier this month. He also sought to trade Thailand's fuel for
Myanmar's natural gas.
</P>
<P>
But Rangoon maintained that the issue must be considered by the
joint Thai-Myanmar trade committee.
</P>
<P>
Thai Chamber of Commerce President Vichian Tejapaibon, who
accompanied Pravich on the visit, said the Thai private sector
intends to invest in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Thai businessmen are conducting a feasibility study on the
production of food, clothes and furniture, using local materials,
and of building bonded warehouses in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
However, Thai traders and investors in Myanmar are battling
hard to survive, given the absence of foreign direct investment in
the country since the regional financial crisis began in July last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
