<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's External Trade Drops Further in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Statistics released by
Singapore's Trade Development Board (TDB) Monday show that the
country's external trade experienced further decline in November,
registering a fall of 14.5, 7.3 and 21.4 percent respectively in
the volume of total trade, exports and imports over a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Compared with November 1997, non-oil domestic exports (NODX)
continued to dive, decreasing by 3.3 percent in November,
following a marginal growth of 0.3 percent in October and
highlighting a significant slowdown in growth of NODX to the EU.
</P>
<P>
Electronic exports remained weak contracting by 4.9 percent and
domestic exports of non-electronics also trended downwards
expanding by an anemic 0.5 percent after a subdued 3.6 percent
growth in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
November also saw domestic exports of oil shrinking by 12.1
percent and non-oil re-exports (NORX) contracting by 11.2 percent
over a year ago.
</P>
<P>
In November, NORX to the U.S. increased marginally by 0.6
percent while that to the EU contracted by 7.1 percent and NORX to
major Asian destinations, viz. Malaysia, Thailand, South Korea,
Hong Kong and Taiwan, continued to decline, reflecting depressed
economic conditions in these markets.
</P>
<P>
Non-oil imports excluding lumpy items such as aircraft and
ships continued to decline, falling by 20.5 percent in November
1998 compared to November 1997.
</P>
<P>
Of the top five traditional NODX markets, NODX to the U.S.
continued to weaken, shrinking further by 5.4 percent in November
over a year ago. The growth of NODX to the EU moderated to 10.1
percent from 20.0 percent in the preceding month while NODX to
Malaysia, Japan and Hong Kong continued to plummet by eight, 10.5
and 23.9 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's NODX to emerging markets increased marginally by
0.1 percent in November with China market outstanding in a
nine-percent rise and Latin American and Eastern European markets
shrinking significantly.
</P>
<P>
TDB attributed the fall in the country's external trade in
November to the worsening economic conditions in the five
crisis-ridden economies, namely, Japan, Malaysia, Hong Kong,
Thailand and South Korea, which account for 42.8 percent of
Singapore's trade, as well as to lackluster global demand for
certain electronic products which continued to take its toll on
Singapore's external trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Softer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 21 (Xinhua) --The Australian share market
closed weaker Monday on the combination of some caution arising
from the impeachment of U.S. President Bill Clinton and lower
volumes leading into the holiday season.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index dropped 11.3 points to 2,738.0, with
the U.S. market Monday night likely to react to the impeachment of
Clinton by the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
"The events in the States over the weekend have made people a
little bit on the cautious side and going into the holiday period
the market tends to quiet down a bit," Sam Panetta from Shaw
Stockbroking said.
</P>
<P>
"I think it (the U.S. financial market) could have an initial
reaction downwards but any large selling will be short-lived and
the market will pick up soon afterwards," he said.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index dropped 19.3 points to 4,912.6, with
further strong activity in the telecommunications sector.
</P>
<P>
ANZ bank led the banking sector, rising 22.3 cents to 10.75
Australian dollars after its annual meeting was told of progress
in increasing profit in this financial year, and that provision
for Asian bad debts would also be lower.
</P>
<P>
Westpac bank was down 1.5 cents at 10.45 Australian dollars on
turnover of 7.2 million shares, National Australia Bank dropped 20
cents to 24.60 Australian dollars, and Commonwealth Bank of
Australia was up 8.6 cents at 22.20 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index dropped 4.8 points to 960.8 with gold
stocks dragging it lower.
</P>
<P>
The gold index fell 22.2 points to 1,097.0 as the bullion price
slid 1.70 U.S. dollars per ounce to 289.80 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Australia's leading company BHP rose ten cents to 12.10
Australian dollars while global miner Rio Tinto finished 7.4 cents
lower at 18.826 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was a light 292.04 million shares traded at a value of
494.99 million U.S. dollars, with 462 rises, 628 falls and 367
steady.  
</P>
</TEXT>
