<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Transform "Shacks" into Comfortable Living Quarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 21 (Xinhua) -- A large-scale construction
campaign began today in Shanghai, China's largest industrial
center, to transform old neighborhoods into new and more
comfortable living quarters in about five years.
</P>
<P>
The China Ocean Shipping Corporation (Shanghai) Industry Co.,
Ltd. will invest six billion yuan into this effort, along with the
city's Putuo District.
</P>
<P>
The project is aimed at improving housing conditions in three
major residential quarters adjacent to the Shanghai Railway
Station, where old shack-like dwellings cover an area of 49.5
hectares.
</P>
<P>
Today's opening ceremony, attended by Huang Ju, member of the
Political Bureau of the Central Committee of the Communist Party
of China (CPC) and secretary of the city's CPC committee, and
Mayor Xu Kuangdi, marked the beginning of the city government's
ambitious plan to transform 3.65 million square meters of inferior
housing.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, with a current population of more than 13 million,
has long been plagued by housing problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
