<HEADLINE> Jordan Calls for Review of Sanctions on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Crown Prince and the
Regent Hassan Ibn Talal has said that sanctions on Iraq should be
reviewed, taking humanitarian needs of the Iraqi people into
consideration.
</P>
<P>
During a visit to the Iraqi-Jordanian border Sunday evening, he
stressed the need for the resumption of dialog between Iraq and
the world community and for a definition of the political
objectives of the world community in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Hassan said that the cessation of military strikes on Iraq
will lead to the resumption of dialog.
</P>
<P>
Charity organizations of the world are calling for public
donations for the Iraqis, he said, adding this is not a substitute
for the lifting of sanctions, which had been imposed on Iraq
following its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The crown prince said that the kingdom is deeply concerned
for the essential services in Iraq, expressing relief that
infrastructure services like water and electricity had not been
affected by the strikes.
</P>
<P>
Accompanying the Regent during the tour, Jordanian Prime
Minister Fayez Tarawneh said the Jordanian-Iraqi border will
remain open to the Iraqis as it was during the just-concluded
United States-British air attacks on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh said the Jordanian government and people share the
feeling of solidarity with the Iraqi people and understand the
injustice Iraq had suffered during the past decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
