<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Seeks International Financial Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Australia seeks better
supervision of the international financial system and increased
transparency in world market dealings, according to a report
released Monday by Australian Prime Minister John Howard.
</P>
<P>
During a ceremony to launch the report, the Australian prime
minister committed his government to actively pursuing many of the
suggestions included in the report by a task force he established
two months ago to look at international financial reforms.
</P>
<P>
Howard said the report would be forwarded to world leaders in
the coming new year.
</P>
<P>
He said the Group of 22 nations, or G22, including seven
industrialized countries, China and Australia, would be the
"centerpiece of international efforts to get greater transparency
and to achieve some of the reforms" in financial dealings.
</P>
<P>
The task force proposed establishment of a working group to
examine appropriate disclosure standards for highly leveraged
hedge funds, and also suggested Australia play an active role in
the establishment of a working group on improved crisis
management.
</P>
<P>
The task force identified key principles for reforming the
international financial system so as to produce greater stability
and capital flows and minimize the risk of future crises.
</P>
<P>
The report proposed that countries prepare "transparency"
reports which indicate the extent to which they meet recognized
disclosure standards.
</P>
<P>
It also recommended encouraging international efforts to
increase trade finance for the crisis economies and providing
technical assistance to facilitate bank and corporate
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
The report also suggested providing technical assistance to
regional economies on developing and managing a sovereign bond
market.
</P>
<P>
One of the recommendations was that countries should be
encouraged to remove any distortions, such as tax incentives
favoring short-term capital flows.
</P>
<P>
Reserve Bank of Australia Governor Ian Macfarlane, the heads of
several government departments and senior representatives from the
Australian banking and financial sectors, made up the task force.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said Australia was in a position to argue
the cause of financial sector reform in the international arena
because of the strength of the domestic financial system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
