<HEADLINE> Islamic Militants Claim Responsibility for Recent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 21 (Xinhua) -- A group of Islamic militants
have claimed responsibility for the recent murders of an Iranian
opposition leader and several dissident writers in Tehran, local
daily Zan (Women) reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The group, called "Fadayan-e Islam Nab Mohammadi Mostafa Navab"
(Islamic Volunteers of His Excellency Pure Mohammad Mostafa), has
issued a statement claiming responsibility for the killings, the
daily said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the group took the responsibility for
the killings of veteran opposition leader Darius Forouhar and his
wife, two dissident writers Mohammad Mokhtari and Mohammad Jafar
Pouyandeh.
</P>
<P>
Forouhar, secretary general of the Iran Nation Party, and his
wife Parvaneh Eskandari were stabbed to death at home in northern
Tehran in late November. Mokhtari and Pouyandeh were found dead,
apparently strangled, after missing for days earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
"The revolutionary executions were a warning to those
mercenary writers and those against (Islamic) values," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The identity of the group is not clear for the Iranian public
so far. Last month, it also claimed responsibility for the attack
on a group of 13 American businessmen in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Interior Minister Mostafa Tajzadeh said on Thursday
that the Iranian authorities have found certain clues about the
recent killings.
</P>
<P>
"We know that they are not foreign nationals but Iranians,
whom we do not yet know enough about," he said, adding that
a special committee comprising deputy interior and intelligence
ministers and security officials has been formed to probe into
the killings.
</P>
<P>
Several other prominent intellectuals were also slayed or
missing during the past weeks.
</P>
<P>
Conservative hardliners, who take most of the key positions in
the country, have earlier accused "foreign agents," specifically
Israel, and an exiled dissident group of carrying out the killings
of these government critics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
