<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Latin America Fights to Resist Financial Turmoil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Economic growth of Latin
America this year has been under pounding pressure due to the
Asian financial crisis that has gone on for one year and a half,
and the Russian financial crisis breaking out not long ago.
</P>
<P>
In order to prevent the financial crisis from lavishing the
region, countries in Latin America have taken measures to adjust
domestic economy, gain international support and strive for a
sustainable economic development.
</P>
<P>
Affected by the financial crisis, Latin America has witnessed a
sharp drop in exports and surge in trade deficit in 1988. Among
countries that are affected remarkably, Brazil, Mexico and
Argentina will register an annual trade deficit of more than six
billion U.S. dollars, and Chile, three billion dollars, three
times that of 1997.
</P>
<P>
There are two key reasons for this situation:
</P>
<P>
One is that exports to the Asian countries in financial crisis
have greatly decreased. Another is that the devaluation of
currencies has rendered Latin American exports less competitive.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the continued low prices of primary products such
as oil, copper and coffee on the international market are also
reasons for the decreasing income of Latin America. For instance,
Venezuela is expected to experience a 6-billion-dollar drop in its
oil earning while Chile will lose 1.6 billion in its copper export
due to depressed prices this year.
</P>
<P>
The Russian financial chaos breaking out in August this year
has affected almost the whole of Latin America with Brazil hit the
hardest. In mid-September, its stock markets of Sao Paulo and Rio
de Janeiro slumped and the total market value shrank from 255
billion dollars to 145 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Brazil's foreign capital outflowed by about 30
billion dollars and foreign reserves dropped from its peak 74
billion dollars to 45 billion dollars, exposing its currency to
great pressure of devaluation.
</P>
<P>
Like the stock markets in Brazil, those in Mexico, Argentina
and some others fared no better.
</P>
<P>
To avoid Southeast Asia-type financial crisis, Latin American
countries have regulated the pace of economic growth and adopted
other positive measures.
</P>
<P>
First, strengthening the macro-economic control and
administration of financial markets.
</P>
<P>
The majority of Latin American countries, including Brazil,
Mexico, Chile and Venezuela, have cut down public expenditure and
financial deficit. Along with the changes on the international
market, they have also strengthened their supervision over capital
markets and enhanced bank interest rates to encourage savings
deposits.
</P>
<P>
All these have played a vital role in helping the countries to
balance their budget and regular expenditure, moderately stabilize
their currencies, limit the transient investments, minimize their
dependence on foreign capital and enhance their resistance to
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Second, adjusting the export strategy adequately and timely.
</P>
<P>
Facing serious challenges in their foreign trade, the Latin
American countries have made great efforts in expanding their
international markets and diversifying export
products. Specifically, they have strengthened trade ties with the
European Union, urged the medium- and small-size businesses to go
international and promoted exports of non-traditional products,
all designed to strengthen international competitiveness and off
set loss caused by falling raw materials prices.
</P>
<P>
Third, promoting regional cooperation and seeking outside
support.
</P>
<P>
To deal with the serious financial turmoil, Latin American
countries have worked closely among themselves while wooing
support from international financial facilities and the Group of
Seven.
</P>
<P>
In mid-September, financial ministers and central bankers from
nine countries including Brazil, Argentina, Mexico and Chile, met
with officials from the United States, Canada and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Within some two months, through tough negotiations, Brazil
landed a 41.5-billion-dollar loan from the IMF for the next three
years. This money will be vital in revitalizing Brazil's economy
and promoting financial stability of the region as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Latin America has done a great deal. With a relatively solid
economic foundation coupled with rapid and effective preventive
measures, the financial chaos has now been eased and crisis
stopped.
</P>
<P>
Quite a few international economic organizations are convinced
of Latin America's economic vitality despite the slowdown of its
development.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that with the only exception of Venezuela,
whose GDP will drop by one percent, the whole region will still be
crowned with a continued GDP growth of eight percent this year,
2.5 percent above that of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
