<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 09:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Asks Butler to Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has accused Richard
Butler, the chief U.N. weapons inspector in Iraq, of being a
troublemaker and asked him to quit.
</P>
<P>
"Butler has lost his credibility, as his stint has become to go
to Iraq to stir up a new problem," the Egyptian Gazette newspaper
quoted Foreign Minister Amr Moussa as saying.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters Sunday, Moussa maintained that it is in
the interest of all that Butler's mission would come to an end.
</P>
<P>
Butler leads the United Nations Special Commission, or UNSCOM,
in charge of overseeing the elimination of Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction, namely the nuclear, chemical and biological weapons
and long-range missiles.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM must certify that Iraq has destroyed all the banned
weapons before the U.N. Security Council can lift the sanctions
imposed on the country after its invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Butler said last week in a report submitted to the U.N. that
Baghdad has failed to cooperate fully with the U.N. arms
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The report was cited by the United States and Britain as
justification for a four-day sustained missile attack on Iraq
since Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
"We should blame the U.N. Special Commission for its failure to
do its job in the proper way. Butler's stand and his performance
were not up to the standard," Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
Butler or whoever would replace him should not work
independently from the U.N., he stressed, adding that the whole
situation and the arms inspections should be reviewed thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
"Can anyone believe that the international community has spent
all this time, money and effort without reaching solid facts that
can help close any of the files on the Iraqi weapons?" Moussa
wondered. 
</P>
</TEXT>
