<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, December 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME -- The European Union (EU) needs to adjust its foreign
policy and security arrangements following the members' dissonant
views on the U.S.-British strikes on Iraq, Italian Foreign
Minister Lamberto Dini said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Foreign Affairs Committee of the Lower House,
Dini said Europe's dissonant views about the strikes and EU's
collective silence have highlighted an "emergency." He believed
that London's participation in the U.S.-led air attacks on Iraq
constituted a clear choice of putting Britain's relationship with
Washington over its ties with the EU. (Italy-EU-Iraq)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- With the impeachment of U.S. President Bill
Clinton now in their hands, senators vowed Sunday to move quickly
although they disagreed on the format -- speedy trial or immediate
censure.
</P>
<P>
Democratic Party senators generally favored censure, while
Republican Party senators leaned toward at least a brief trial.
Both said the upper chamber of Congress had to restore civility
and "political sanity" to the process. (US-Senate-Trial)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Nizar Hamdoon, Iraq's ambassador to the
United Nations, said Sunday that the U.S.-led military strikes
against Iraq killed or wounded thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Hamdoon said, "There has been enormous
damage, mainly to the civilian infrastructure and to human life. I
am told that the casualties are in thousands, in terms of people
who were killed or wounded. But we do not have any final figures."
Hamdoon said Iraq would ask the United Nations Security Council to
lift immediately the economic sanctions which had been in place
for eight years. (UN-Iraq-Casualties) 
</P>
