<HEADLINE> Danish Line to Introduce 21-Day Service to E. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Nordana, the Danish shipping
line which began a direct east Africa-Europe service in June this
year, is restructuring the service to a 21-day frequency from the
initial fortnightly service.
</P>
<P>
Reshadi Noor, the Ship's Agency Department Manager of
Panalpina, said the move had been necessitated by the increased
demand on break-bulk as opposed to containerized cargo services.
Pahanlpina is the line's Mombasa ground agent.
</P>
<P>
The line will also replace the faster Astrakhan Mark III class
vessels with Mark II, which are more economical, the East African
weekly newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Mark II vessels have larger holds and hatch openings, fast
cranes with heavy lift facilities and ample container space
including refrigerated units and can cope well with the transit
time of 19 days between Europe and east Africa.
</P>
<P>
Noor said the restructuring program has sparked rumors within
the industry that Nordana was pulling out of the trade.
</P>
<P>
"This was never the case. All we did was adopt a service
which would be more suited for our clientele," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mv (motor vessel) Nordana Karlina, the first vessel on the
restructured service, is due at the port of Mombasa on December
27, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The ship will offload some 9,367 tons of import cargo
including motor cars, malt for the local brewing industry, iron
coils, steel billets and 100 containers.
</P>
<P>
The second vessel, Nordana Captain P, is expected in Mombasa
on January 18, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
