<HEADLINE> Japan's Trade Surplus Down in Twenty Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Japan's merchandise trade
surplus in November fell by 15.1 percent from a year earlier to
902 billion yen (about 7.6 billion U.S. dollars), marking the
first drop in 20 months, the Finance Ministry said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry attributed the decline to a shrinkage in exports
to the United States, Japanese exporters' largest market. Japan's
exports to the U.S. fell for the first time in two years and eight
months.
</P>
<P>
Japan's overall exports dropped by 12.7 percent to 3,688.9
billion yen (about 31.2 billion dollars), while imports fell by
11.9 percent to 2,786.9 billion yen (about 23.6 billion dollars),
the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Japan's politically sensitive trade surplus with the
U.S. gained only 0.9 percent in November to 488.2 billion yen
(about 4.1 billion dollars), compared with a 31.9-percent jump in
the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Japan's trade surplus with Asian economies plummeted 66.3
percent to 184.7 billion yen (about 1.6 billion dollars), while
that with the 15-member European Union contracted 2.6 percent to
272.8 billion yen (about 2.3 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The yen averaged 118.36 to the U.S. dollar in the latest
reporting month, up 3.4 percent from a year earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Traffic Accidents Cost S. Africa Dear Daily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Traffic accidents are
costing South Africa more than 40 million Rand (6.6 million U.S.
Dollars) a day, up from a staggering five million Dollars five
years ago, the Star daily reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Average of 30 people were killed each day on South Africa's
roads this decade, according to a survey by the the National
Trauman Research Program (NTRP).
</P>
<P>
An average of 100 people were seriously injured each day and
an average of 250 people suffered lesser injuries, the survey
showed.
</P>
<P>
Eric Buch, deputy director-general of the health department in
Gauteng Province, was quoted as saying that road accidents had a
major impact on health-care costs and services.
</P>
<P>
"The orthopaedic and neurosurgery wards are especially
pressured," he said.
</P>
<P>
People hospitalized with traffic trauma usually had severe
injuries, requiring protracted and expensive treatment. However,
only about 5.5 percent of the related costs were recovered from
patients, said Johan van der Spuy of the NTRP.
</P>
<P>
The NTRP identified speed, alcohol and other substance abuse,
as well as failure to wear seat belts and protective head gear in
the case of motorcycles and bicycles, as contributing factors to
the high fatality rates on South African roads.
</P>
<P>
Pedestrians also accounted for about 40 percent of annual road
fatalities, said Van der Spuy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
