<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nyerere to Report Progress in Burundi Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Julius Nyerere,
mediator of the Burundi crisis, will report the achievement from
the peace talks by warring parties to the nations which imposed
economic sanctions on Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Sources from Tanzanian northern town of Arusha, where three
rounds of peace talks have been held, told Xinhua Monday in a
telephone interview that preparations are well under way for the
fourth round of talks scheduled on January 18 in Arusha.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere, founding president of Tanzania, told a closing
session by three committees for the peace talks over the weekend
that he will report the progress achieved so far to the leaders
of the Great Lakes nations as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The sweeping sanctions were imposed by seven neighboring
nations in August 1996 when retired Major Pierre Buyoya was
rethroned following a military coup by the Tutsi-led army in late
July.
</P>
<P>
They demanded Buyoya to restore constitutional order and open
talks with the major ethnic Hutu oppositions.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere also said that delegates from all the factions in
Burundi will debate on the reconstruction and development of the
tiny central African country in the forthcoming talks.
</P>
<P>
Since June, delegates from the Burundi government, parties and
rebel groups have met for three rounds of talks in Arusha in a
way to seek an end to the bloody tribal conflicts.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 150,000 Burundians, mostly civilians, have been
killed since 1993 when the first ethnic Hutu president Melchior
Ndadaye was assassinated in a military coup.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Burundi Minister for Peace Process Ambroise
Niyonsaba was quoted as saying in Arusha over the weekend that he
expected the sanctions will be lifted soon.
</P>
<P>
"Nyerere's remark gives me a hope that he will do something to
help in lifting the economic embargo against my country," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
