<HEADLINE> S. African Mining Giant Buys Zambian Copper Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 21 (Xinhua) -- South African mining
giant Anglo American Corporation (ACC) has signed a deal to buy
Zambia's state-owned copper mines, the Citizen newspaper reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The AAC would take over Nchanga, Nkana and Konkola mines, the
remaining major assets of Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines, the
country's sole mining conglomerate, the paper quoted Zambian
Finance Minister Edith Nawakwi as saying Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The South African investors have pledged to pump in 300
million U.S. Dollars in three years into the three mines and buy
the nearby Konkola Deep mine a year later with a pledged
investment of 800 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Konkola Deep mine is said to be the key to the future
viability of copper mining in Zambia at a time of low copper
prices on world commodity markets.
</P>
<P>
The ACC is expected to start operation in the Zambian mines by
March next year.
</P>
<P>
Zambia had been under intense pressure from its donors to sell
off the inefficient and overmanned mines.
</P>
<P>
The mines sold to the ACC were estimated to be losing up to
one million Dollars a day in recent weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
