<HEADLINE> Turkish PM-Designate Returns Mandate to Form </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister
designate Bulent Ecevit announced here Monday that he had
returned his mandate for a government formation to President
Suleyman Demirel.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit, also leader of the Democratic Left Party (DSP), the
fourth biggest party in the parliament, was assigned by Demirel
to form the 56th coalition government on December 2 after the
former minority government led by Mesut Yilmaz collapsed for his
corruption scandals on November 25.
</P>
<P>
Despite Ecevit's 17-day consultation with the political parties
in parliament, his efforts fell short of coming up with a
government that could pass a confidence vote in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The opposition True Path Party (DYP) Chairwoman, Tansu Ciller
and Republican People's Party (CHP) leader Deniz Baykal had
rejected three proposals for a coalition to be formed by the
Motherland Party (ANAP), the DYP and the DSP, a DSP minority
government and the broad-based government.
</P>
<P>
The time remaining for political parties to form a government
that could win a vote of confidence from parliament is now less
than three weeks.
</P>
<P>
If a government that could win a confidence vote from
parliament can not be formed by January 10, 1999, the Turkish
president will have the right to form a government that would not
require a confidence vote in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish constitution requires a designated prime minister
to form a new government within 45 days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
