<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Marketers Double Fuel Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Petroleum products marketers in
Nigeria have increased the official pump price of petroleum from
11 Naira (about 0.13 U.S. Dollar) to 25 Naira per liter at the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
The price increase followed last week's proposed deregulation
of commodity prices by the Nigerian government, The Post Express
newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Chief of General Staff Rear Admiral Mike Akhigbe said in
capital Abuja last Thursday that the government had no plans to
hike fuel price, but would allow marketers to fix an appropriate
price for the commodity.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has been gripped by a protracted fuel crisis all over
the country since 1996, leading to arbitrary hike in transport
fares and near-collapse of socio-economic activities.
</P>
<P>
Although the country is the sixth largest oil producer in the
world with a production capacity of 2.3 million barrels per day,
all its four refineries in the country broke down for technical
hitches, leading to severe scarcity of oil supply in the country.
</P>
<P>
There has been speculations that the Nigerian government would
increase fuel price in its 1999 budget to make up for the budget
deficit in 1998 because of the falling price of crude oil at the
international market.
</P>
<P>
The oil price increase has been a source of heated debate
between the government and labor groups in this west African
country as the development has the potentials to ignite a
widespread crisis.
</P>
<P>
When the price was adjusted in 1994, it generated serious
crisis which threatened the socio-political peace of the nation,
prompting the establishment of the Petroleum Trust Fund to manage
the extra funds realized by the price increase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
