<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Finance Minister Reviews Reforms of Past 20 Years (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 21 (Xinhua) -- In a lengthy article entitled
"China's Finances in the Reforms and Opening-up" in today's
People's Daily, Finance Minister Xiang Huaicheng reviews what
financial reforms have achieved in the past two decades as well as
the problems that still exist.
</P>
<P>
The veteran economist says that China has basically established
a finance and taxation framework that meets the requirements of
the socialist market economy in the process of its economic
reform. One of the major breakthroughs was the break with the
highly-centralized finance system of the planned economy and the
introduction of a revenue-sharing taxation system for the central
and local governments.
</P>
<P>
The reforms have also led to more diverse tax categories, and
more rational distribution, budget, and accounting practices, he
says, and continued fast growth in the economy and increased
finance reforms have provided a solid foundation for fairly high
growth rate in revenues.
</P>
<P>
China's revenues rose to 865.1 billion yuan (104.2 billion
U.S. dollars) in 1997, as opposed to 113.2 billion yuan in 1978,
for an annual growth rate of 11.3 percent. The growth has actually
been 18.8 percent since 1994 when the revenue-sharing system was
put into practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Finance Minister Reviews Reforms of Past 20 Years (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The increased revenues have increased the country's financial
strength, pushing expenditures to 923.3 billion yuan in 1997,
compared with 112.2 billion yuan in 1978.
</P>
<P>
But, in spite of the progress, he says, state financial power
is still clearly inadequate, causing the central government's
deficit to grow to 55.8 billion yuan in 1997 from 9.8 billion yuan
in 1979, and central government debts to 247.7 billion yuan in
1997 from 8.4 billion yuan in 1982.
</P>
<P>
One major task, he says, is to make an effort to gradually
increase the proportion of revenues in the GNP and revenues of the
central government out of total revenues to arrive at more solid
and balanced state finances.
</P>
<P>
To deal with problems arising from the Asian financial crisis
and decreased domestic demand, he says, the Chinese government is
pursuing an active financial policy designed to stimulate the
economy and market demand. But, from a mid-term and long-term
perspective, the government has to stick to an appropriately tight
financial policy with emphasis on increased revenues and thrift.
</P>
<P>
Future reforms in the finance and tax systems will focus on
getting rid of illegal fees and turning reasonable fees into
taxes, he says, and is asking for a greater effort in improving
the revenue-sharing tax system and the tax-collection practices.
</P>
<P>
He has also asked for improvements in the budget management
system by gradually establishing public budget, state-owned
capital, and social security budget systems, and an improved
social security system with a re-employment system, pension
system, medical-care system, and minimum wage system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
