<HEADLINE> Swede Succeeds Skiing to South Pole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Ola Skinnarmo of Sweden
arrived at the South Pole by skiing at 17:00 GMT on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Skinnarmo, 26, set out from the coast of the Weddell Sea off
the Antarctic seven weeks ago. The route from the coast to the
Pole is 1,200 kilometers long.
</P>
<P>
He got to the destination 10 days prior to the schedule.
</P>
<P>
He said he was not threatened by the severe coldness and the
only thing he could not stand was that he hasn't taken a bath for
seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
On December 14, 1914, Norwegian Roald Amundsen became the
first man who arrived at the South Pole by skiing solely. 
