<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Public Debt Rises: C. Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's public debt rose to
483.8 billion Shillings (8.06 billion U.S. Dollars) or 68 percent
of the gross domestic product (GDP) at the end of October from
7.9 billion Dollars or 75 percent of the GDP in June.
</P>
<P>
According to the December issue of the Monthly Economic Review
published by the Central Bank of Kenya available here Monday,
there is a 108 million Dollars net increase in domestic debt and
a 31 million Dollars in net decline in foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
The foreign debt decrease was a result of the repayment of 115
million Dollars to external creditors and 83 million Dollars
disbursements, says the review.
</P>
<P>
It was the fourth consecutive month in which domestic debt
rose, the review says, adding that the rising debt is attributed
to the government's increased budgetary financing requirements as
well as the need to service external debts.
</P>
<P>
Of the 8.06-billion-Dollar public debt, domestic debt
accounted for 2.5 billion Dollars, or 31.8 percent of the total,
while the foreign debt stood at 5.5 billion Dollars, 68.2 percent
of the total,
</P>
<P>
The review notes that most of the foreign debt is long-term
and concessional. In terms of composition, three billion Dollars
were owed to multilateral creditors and 2.1 billion Dollars to
bilateral creditors, and the rest was in both commercial bank
loans and export credit.
</P>
<P>
The review says overall month-to-month inflation declined in
November, remaining within the single-digit range.
</P>
<P>
The inflation decline is attributed to the slowdown in the
expansion of money supply, the stability of the Shilling and the
improved supply of basic foodstuffs, particularly during the last
quarter of the year, according to the central bank report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
