<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Customs Undergoes Drastic Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHUHAI, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Zhuhai, a special economic
zone which used to be a fishing village two decades ago, has
become the second largest entry and exit for international
travelers with the development of its Gongbei Port.
</P>
<P>
Gongbei Port is a large one with 12 docks. Between 1978 and
1997, travelers handled by the customs rose 49 times, increasing
from 590,000 to 2.96 million. In 1997, it handled 2.1 million
tons of cargo, 44.6 items more than that in 1978.
</P>
<P>
According to Liu Hao, head of the Gongbei Customs, the people
and cargo handled by the customs have undergone great changes
since the launching of the reform and opening up two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
Before the opening up, most of the people going through the
customs are those coming to see their relatives in the inland
area from Hong Kong and Macao. What they brought in were mostly
daily necessities and electronic appliances; they took out mostly
special local farm products.
</P>
<P>
Now people not only come from Hong Kong and Macao, but also
from elsewhere in the world. They come as tourists and business
people.
</P>
<P>
Liu said exports from the inland area two decades ago were
mostly farm products, sand and stones. Now exports also include
electronic and medical products as well as machinery.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Drive Seen to End Burundi Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Efforts to negotiate the
lifting of two-year-old sanctions on Burundi have received a
fresh impetus following former Tanzanian president Julius
Nyerere's brief visit to Nairobi at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere, who was appointed by the Organization of African
Unity (OAU) as the peace facilitator in the Burundi issue, held
talks with Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi Saturday over this
matter and other things, a Kenyan Foreign Ministry official
confirmed Monday.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere has reportedly managed to get both Tanzania's
President Benjamin Mkapa and Uganda's President Yoweri Museveni
to soften their opposition to the lifting of the sanctions, the
official, who refused to be named, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The new initiative comes in the wake of a rise in incidents of
sanction-busting by a business community frustrated by the
embargo.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Major General Salim Saleh, a brother to Museveni,
announced he was negotiating for a contract to supply meat worth
10 million U.S. Dollars to Burundi despite the embargo.
</P>
<P>
"I am in the advanced stages of negotiating the contract,"
Ugandan papers quoted Saleh as saying.
</P>
<P>
Although officials in the Kenyan, Ugandan and Tanzanian
ministries of foreign affairs said the sanctions are still on,
local media said that the lobby pushing for lifting of the
sanctions was gaining strength.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were imposed on Burundi by east African states
in August 1996 following a Tutsi-led military coup staged by
Major Pierre Buyoya, which ousted the civilian government of
President Sylvestre Ntibantunganya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
