<HEADLINE> China Sees Stable Rise in Coal Production and Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 21 (Xinhua) -- China expects to maintain
stable coal production and exports this year by turning out 1.35
billion tons of coal and exporting 35 million tons, according to a
senior official with the China State Administration of Coal
Industry.
</P>
<P>
These figures represent one-third of the world's total output,
and six percent of the world's total coal trade, respectively, the
official added.
</P>
<P>
At present, supply exceeds demand in coal markets both at home
and abroad, and the dwindling demand for coal in Southeast Asian
countries has affected China's coal exports.
</P>
<P>
However, the Chinese government has put in place a series of
supporting and encouraging policies and measures which have
effectively boosted the country's coal exports, said the official.
</P>
<P>
He noted that since the reshaping of the coal-industry system in
the first half of this year, China's coal mines have become more
growth oriented, while their staffs have been cut by a wide margin.
</P>
<P>
Statistics shows that some 870,000 workers and staff in key
coal mines have been laid off or transferred to other jobs over
the past five years.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, diversified economic operations have
contributed significantly to the sound development of coal mines
this year, said the official.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this year, the country's coal-related diversified
economic enterprises is expected to grow to 17,000, employing a
total of over 1.8 million people.
</P>
<P>
He expects these diversified economic enterprises to produce
output value and economic returns totalling 44.5 billion yuan, or
57 percent of the total output value produced by coal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
