<HEADLINE> Zambia's Unions Welcome Copper Mines Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The Zambia Congress of Trade
Unions (ZCTU) has welcomed the sale of Nchanga and Nkana mines,
which account for two-third of Zambia's total copper mine assets.
</P>
<P>
ZCTU President Fackson Shamenda said here Sunday that if it is
true the sale of the mines has been concluded, it is a welcome
move as the mines are becoming a burden to the nation.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia newspaper Monday quoted him as saying that the
sale price is not important in comparison with burden the mines
have become.
</P>
<P>
Shamenda said recapitalization of the mines will help
reactivate economic activities of the country's copper industry,
which earns 80 percent of Zambia's foreign exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
He hoped the donors will now release the money pledged as they
had been using the sale of the mines as a pre-condition for
funding.
</P>
<P>
"We only hope they will not come up with another excuse to
hold on to the money," he said.
</P>
<P>
The two mines together with Konkola mine have been sold to
Anglo-American Corporation (ACC) at the price of 72 million U.S.
Dollars and the new owner are expected to take them over by the
end of March next year, Zambian Finance Minister Edith Nawakwi
said last week.
</P>
<P>
In May this year, donors pledged to give the country an aid of
530 million Dollars. However, they have withheld the money to
press the Zambian government to speed up the privatization of the
Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM).
</P>
<P>
Due to disagreement over the cost of Nkana and Nchanga mines,
Zambia discontinued the negotiations with Kafue Consortium last
April over the sale of the two biggest mines in the country.
</P>
<P>
It was reported earlier that Zambia originally demanded 400
millions Dollars for the two mines from Kafue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
