<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Enters Finance Arrangement With Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Monday signed
with Japan's Nomura International and the Sumitomo Bank Ltd. a
finance deal involving 74 billion yen (563.157 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's Second Finance Minister Mustapa Mohamed, Head of
Asia Oceania of the Nomura International Daisuke Takeuchi and
General Manager of International Finance of The Sumitomo Bank
Tsutomu Asano signed the documents in relation to the deal on
behalf of their respective authorities.
</P>
<P>
The structured finance arrangement involves the Malaysian
government borrowing the amount from the Sumitomo Bank with
Japan's Ministry of International Trade and Industry (MITI)
issuing an insurance policy as collateral for the loan.
</P>
<P>
Of the loan, 90 percent or 66.6 billion yen (506.841 million
U.S. dollars) is funded by the issue of euro yen notes in capital
markets, which was arranged by Nomura International, while the
rest 10 percent or 7.4 billion yen (56.315 million U.S. dollars)
would be privately placed.
</P>
<P>
Mustapa said on the occasion that the structured loan
represented the first and only international market borrowing for
Malaysia this year.
</P>
<P>
He said the loan represented the first time that any country
had used the sovereignty of another country to raise funds from
the international capital market.
</P>
<P>
He said the loan is one of the several efforts on the Malaysian
part to raise funds to finance its economic recovery and the
proceeds of this loan will be used to finance development
projects.
</P>
<P>
Mustapa told reporters after the signing here that Malaysia had
also requested 5 billion U.S. dollars under Japan's Miyazawa
initiative to help countries affected by the economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
He said the Economic Planning Unit of the Prime Minister's
Department has made the request for the loan which would be used
to partly finance the 1999 budget deficit of 16.2 billion ringgit
(4.263 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Miyazawa initiative, announced in September and named after
Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa, is a 30 billion U.S. dollar
financial stimulus package mooted to help ailing Asian economies
affected by the prevailing financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Miyazawa plan is also meant to stabilize and revitalize the
financial system, provide social safety nets for the socially
handicapped, provide economic stimulus to create more jobs for
countries in trouble and cope with the credit crunch in affected
economies.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is also talking with some other multilateral agencies
to borrow money, Mustapa said without naming the agencies, adding
that he was not optimistic that the money would be gotten in the
near future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
