<HEADLINE> China to Further Implement Industrial Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Minister in charge of
the State Economic and Trade Commission Zheng Silin said that
China will further implement industrial restructuring, cutting
out-moded spindles and closing small coal mines, reported the
China Reform News.
</P>
<P>
Zheng made these remarks in a report to 170 deputies of the
Chinese National People's Congress who have just concluded
investigations in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The restructuring will be focused on the textile industry,
said Zheng. About 4.5 million spindles for cotton-spinning will
be cut next year and the number of workers in the industry will
be reduced by 500,000. One million spindles for wool-spinning
will be cut in three years' time.
</P>
<P>
Next year, 25,800 coal mines will be closed and the output of
coal will be reduced by 250 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Zheng also said that the metallurgical industry will undergo a
readjustment in product mix. No new steel- and iron-producing
plants will be established until 2000, with a view to bring about
a better economic returns in the industry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
