<HEADLINE> Zambian Police Intensify Anti-crime Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Zambian police is taking a
number of measures including mobilizing community to prevent the
escalating crimes in capital Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail Monday quoted inspector-general of police
Francis Ndhlovu as saying that "the recent attempts to disrupt
peace and security in Lusaka shall be addressed critically by
police."
</P>
<P>
He said the police have identified the cause of the rising
crime and that strong measures are being instituted aimed at
combating the scourge.
</P>
<P>
The division of Lusaka into manageable zones is one of the
measures by the police in order to intensify night patrols in
most inaccessible compounds where crime is prevalent, according
to him.
</P>
<P>
Ndhlovu said the the police could not adequately curb crime in
the past due to a shortfall of officers in the field and that his
command shall prioritize training of officers to correspond with
the escalation of crime.
</P>
<P>
There will be a heavy presence of police in compounds where
crime is mostly committed, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ndhlovu called on the public to report all crime incidents to
police in good time so that quick action will be taken to cope
with them.
</P>
<P>
Police alone cannot do much in preventing crime, unless the
community get fully involved, he noted. 
</P>
