<HEADLINE> China Unwraps Keyless Safe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese computer experts have
recently developed the country's first safe that opens upon
recognition of the right person's face.
</P>
<P>
The safe was developed by a team of computer experts at the
Department of Computer Science of Harbin Polytechnic University,
and has been granted patent rights.
</P>
<P>
The new safe does not require any key or password, said
Professor Yin Zhenliang, head of the team.
</P>
<P>
Yin said he hit upon the idea of the face-recognition safe
three years ago. At a local financial safety meeting, he was
approached by a banker. The banker suggested a keyless safe,
because the conventional safe is inconvenient. If there were more
than one person in charge of the safe, the lock had to be changed
when one person lost the key.
</P>
<P>
"To open the safe, you simply stand in front of it. The
personal computer connected to the lock looks at you through its
camera, and verifies your looks with the preinstalled information
about the owner's face," explains Yin at a demonstration.
</P>
<P>
He said the computer is accurate. Even twins can be
distinguished.
</P>
<P>
Some banks have already installed the keyless safe. Yin
expects more financial organizations to use the new product, as
most of the major banks have approached him to discuss the p
ossibility of cooperation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
