<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People Of China's Taklimakan Desert Knocking On Modernity's Door </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The people of the world's
second largest desert have begun to embrace modern life with their
television news every day and motor vehicles instead of camels.
</P>
<P>
Ten percent of the households of Daliyabuyi, the largest town
in the Taklimakan Desert, in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region, have cars or trucks, but only 15 years ago,
they didn't even know how a truck worked.
</P>
<P>
They relied on candles for lighting until the early 1990s, but
now get world news from ground satellite stations on 4
Chinese-language channels and 5 Uygur-language channels. The town
has a population of 1,200.
</P>
<P>
More than 6,000 people in the 330,000-square-kilometer desert
were cut off from the outside world for centuries, until the
mid-1950s. A herdsman living on the rim of the desert needed half
a month to walk out of the desert where high dunes kept it
isolated.
</P>
<P>
Domestic animals and wildlife were the main food until the
first half of this century, when people began to get fruits and
flour after 1953, when officials of the new Yutian County
government sent food there.
</P>
<P>
When a road was built across the desert, the lives of people
there underwent great changes. Various commodities started to
appear, along with foreign tourists coming for desert expeditions.
</P>
<P>
Decades ago, a household with 10 family members usually had one
or two padded cotton quilts, but now a household has dozens of
woolen blankets, more than 20 quilts and about 5 carpets as well,
and over 90 percent of school-aged children receive an
education.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
