<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0400 GMT, December 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thailand customs authorities are considering the
possibility of allowing honest exporters to bypass regular customs
procedures.
</P>
<P>
A customs official on Sunday confirmed media reports that
exporters with honest track records will be issued gold cards to
bypass customs checks.
</P>
<P>
Card-holders would be able to ship their cargo immediately and
arrange documents for later audit, said the official.
(Thailand-Customs)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SINGAPORE -- Singapore's retail sales and catering trade inched
up 2.1 and 5.4 percent respectively in October over September
1998, but declined by 10.7 and 4.5 percent respectively compared
to the same period in 1997, according to the data released Sunday
by Singapore Department of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Total value of retail sales in October was estimated at 1,620
million Singapore dollars (981 million U.S. dollars) compared with
1,586 million Singapore dollars (961 million U.S. dollars) in the
September this year.
</P>
<P>
Total value of catering trade in October 1998 was estimated at
256 million Singapore dollars (155 million U.S. dollars), compared
with 243 million Singapore dollars (147 million U.S. dollars)in
the previous month. (Singapore-Retail)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thai women workers, hit hard by the economic
recession, faced family problems because of job losses, a survey
revealed.
</P>
<P>
The mass lay-offs in 1998 mostly took place in the textiles
and electronics industries where 90 percent of workers are women,
according to the survey, made public on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Most of the laid-off workers are aged 40-50 or nearing
retirement. These workers had been working for long periods and
received high payment and welfare, said the survey, conducted by
the Friends of Women Foundation. (Thailand-Women-Unemployment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HARARE -- Barclays bank Sunday said Zimbabwe has the most
unstable peacetime economy in the southern African region due to
continuously plummeting public and business confidence.
</P>
<P>
In its Economic Bulletin for December released in Harare, the
bank said most households had become much poorer in the wake of a
more than 100 percent decline in the value of the exchange rate in
local currency terms, while an inflation rate of 45 percent in
November was among the highest in the region. (Zimbabwe-Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA -- The Ministry of Mines and Energy of Ethiopia
Sunday announced the government's decision to reject the bid for
the privatization of the Kalub Gas Share Company.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry was quoted by the Ethiopian News Agency as saying
that the Ethiopian government has decided to withdraw the bid for
the sale of its stake in the company because it found the bid
results unsatisfactory. (Ethiopia-Privatization-Bid)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Despite various stimulation measures taken by the
government, Israel's economy is expected to rise by only 1.6
percent in 1998, the lowest in the decade due to an emerging
global economic shrink and a restrictive monetary policy
introduced more than two years ago.
</P>
<P>
The figure, given by the Israeli Finance ministry in its latest
report, is based on the country's GDP growth rates in the past
three quarters, namely 1.4 percent in the third quarter, 1.6
percent in the second quarter and 2 percent in the first three
months.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's data also pointed to a remarkable fall in public
consumption and a substantial decline in investments in 1998.
(Israel-Economy-Yearender) 
</P>
