<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Modernize Telephone Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh Telegraph and
Telephone Board (BTTB) has made effective steps to modernize its
telephone systems to ensure that digital lines would be extended
to every subscriber in the country by the beginning of the new
century, The Bangladesh Observer newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
There are about 230,400 telephone lines in the capital city of
Dhaka at present, including 168,900 digital lines and 61,500
analog lines, and the BTTB has planned to replace analog lines
with digital ones by the year 2000, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Over 138,500 new digital telephone lines are going to be
installed by August 1999 in Dhaka, Narayanganj and Savar, both on
the outskirts of the capital, against the number of telephone
demand of 135,000 lines, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
In January 1998, there were about 492,000 telephone lines in
Bangladesh, with a population of 127 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
