<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coastal Pollution Poses Serious Problem in Colombo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The pollution taking place
along the sea coast of the city of Colombo poses a serious problem
needing urgent attention, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Colombo is the only city in Sri Lanka which has a pipe borne
sewage system, said Sarath Perera, director of Surveillance and
Monitoring Division of the Ministry of Fisheries and Aquatic
Resources Development.
</P>
<P>
He said all city sewage is drained to the sea without any
purification treatment due to the lack of refineries.
</P>
<P>
About 25 to 30 million gallons flow into the sea every day. The
13 pumping stations in the city divert the sewage to Madampitiya
in the north of Colombo to be released to the sea.
</P>
<P>
This sewage pipeline which has no refinery facility is over 100
years old. The water pollution affects not only the surface water
but also the underground water, he said.
</P>
<P>
Perera said Sri Lanka should follow a system similar to the
clean rivers system adopted in India where local technology at low
cost is used to prevent river, sea and water pollution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
