<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Elected to Asia Pacific Telecommunity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 21 (Xinhua) -- A Sri Lankan
telecommunications expert has been elected as vice-chairman of the
Asia Pacific Telecommunity (APT) management committee at its 22nd
session held in Bangkok recently, the official Daily News reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report said the election of R.B. Kumarapathirana, director
of the Telecommunications Regulatory Commission of Sri Lanka, is
considered a recognition of Sri Lanka's leading position in Asian
telecom reform.
</P>
<P>
APT, the main institution of regional cooperation in
telecommunications, was set up in 1979 by an inter-governmental
agreement.
</P>
<P>
It is a unique meeting ground for representatives of
governments, regulators, telecom service providers and others
involved in the development of telecommunications, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Since its inception in 1979, the APT has been playing a leading
role in promoting the growth, enhancement of applications and
utilization of telecommunication services in the Asia Pacific
region.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka joined APT on November 1, 1979 and has been an active
member for the past nineteen years. In 1998 Sri Lanka hosted two
APT events, the first South Asian Telecom Regulatory Council
meeting and the Telecom Working Group for South Asia, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The APT management committee which meets once a year is
composed of 29 members, 4 associate members and 39 affiliate
members. It supervises the APT secretariat's functions, and
reviews and approves its work program, annual budget and accounts.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
