<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Mafia Godfather Shot Dead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Ivo Karamanski, 39, known as
"the Godfather of the Bulgarian Mafia," and his 28-year-old
bodyguard were shot dead early Sunday morning in a drunken brawl,
said the Interior Ministry press office.
</P>
<P>
Another two men, aged 33 and 44, were injured and hospitalized,
with one of them in critical condition, the office said.
</P>
<P>
Karamanski and his bodyguards were attending a party in Sofia's
Simeonovo suburb when the incident happened. A quarrel broke out
at around 2:20 a.m. local time on Sunday between drunken
Karamanski and one of the young men who organized the party, and
ended in shooting.
</P>
<P>
The suspected assailant escaped from the scene but was later
arrested.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses denied there had been a drunken row, said
investigator Emil Ivanov on Sunday. Stefan K., the suspect, fired
two shots from a Makarov pistol point-blank at Karamanski's head.
</P>
<P>
The motive of the suspect and whether he has a criminal record
were still unknown, police said, noting that the murderer and
Karamanski knew each other well.
</P>
<P>
Karamanski, a former rower on the national canoe-kayak team,
was the boss of the Korona insurance company, which was considered
as an insurance racket.
</P>
<P>
Karamanski was said to have been involved in many scandals over
shady business and violent crime. He was once arrested in Prague
for involvement in smuggling stolen cars and was remanded in
custody for 17 months in 1995 during an investigation into a
casino robbery.
</P>
<P>
The Special Investigative Service will work on Karamanski's
murder. 
</P>
</TEXT>
