<HEADLINE> IOC New Selection System Looms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 20 (Xinhua) -- International Olympic
Committee president Juan Antonio Samaranch indicated that a new
way of selecting Olympic cities might be in place by next summer,
according to local reports here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The IOC president said that after the bribery scandal widened.
</P>
<P>
"After this scandal, I believe that the IOC as a whole must
accept that the system needs to change and that we can't continue
like this," Samaranch said.
</P>
<P>
A top IOC member, Switzerland's Marc Holder, has estimated
that 5 to 7 percent of the 115 members are open to bribery.
</P>
<P>
Hodler, a former head of the International Ski Federation, is
on the Sion 2006 Bid organizing committee.
</P>
<P>
His accusations of rampant corruption and vote-buying have
rocked the Olympic world.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch said IOC members found guilty of corruption will be
expelled from the organization.
</P>
<P>
"We are not happy with the way of selecting organizing cities
for the games," Samaranch said.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch said the Olympics should follow the example of other
major sports bodies, which leave significant decisions to their
executive committees rather than the full membership.
</P>
<P>
"But it's not easy to ask members to agree to cut off their
own heads," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the light of the current situation, he said it was possible
the IOC members would give the 11-member executive committee
special powers.
</P>
<P>
The new way may apply for the host of the 2006 Winter
Olympics. If successful, the same system would be used for the
2008 Games, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
