<HEADLINE> Italy Urges to Reexamine EU Diplomatic, Security Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. and British unilateral
attacks against Iraq have called for a greater need for the
European Union (EU) to reexamine its joint diplomatic and security
policies, said the Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Foreign Affairs Committee of the Chambers of
Deputies, Dini said that the British participation in the U.S.-led
military operation against Iraq has "fully demonstrated that
British relations with the United States are more important than
its relations with the EU."
</P>
<P>
"Britain has not considered its relations with the EU members
as it participated in the attack," he added.
</P>
<P>
Britain had not notified its EU partners before it participated
in the U.S.-led Operation Desert Fox, a move Italy sees as a
challenge to the formation of the EU diplomatic and security
mechanism.
</P>
<P>
The Italian press believed that the mechanism has become the
most vulnerable part in the process of the EU unification.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Dini also wrote on the la Republica that after the
end of the military attacks, Italy will seek to improve the EU
diplomatic and security mechanisms so that the EU will act
unanimously under similar circumstances.
</P>
<P>
The Italian press said the U.S. military action with an EU
member while bypassing the United Nations, NATO (the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization) and EU has created political
disagreement among Western allies.
</P>
<P>
The EU members should realize that the American superpower
perception has threatened the process of the European unification,
the press added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
