<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: What U.N. Will Do Next to Iraqi Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Washington and London's
announcement on Saturday night to end their four-day airstrikes
against Iraq came before the United Nations Security Council was
to make its first official reaction to what was seen here as a
violation of the U.N. Charter and the norms of the international
law.
</P>
<P>
At the time the United States and Britain started the military
strikes, the Security Council was convening closed-door
consultations on a report by chief U.N. arms inspector Richard
Butler, who accused Iraq of non-cooperation with U.N. arms
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council, shocked by the missile explosions in
Baghdad, held several rounds of emergent talks on the latest
development in the Iraqi crisis, but the council failed to make
any official response to the U.S.-led military action simply due
to strong objections from representatives of the United States and
Britain.
</P>
<P>
Washington and London used force against Iraq without the
authorization from the Security Council, thus posing a serious
challenge to the authority of the United Nations and the Security
Council, which has, under the Charter, primary responsibility for
the maintenance of international peace and security. The U.S.-led
strikes has immediately touched off worldwide condemnation.
</P>
<P>
The 15-member council has decided to meet again on Iraq at
10:30 a.m.(EST) on Monday, U.N. officials said. At present, a
repeated question here is What the council will do next to the
Iraqi crisis?
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that the Security Council is expected to
focus its attention on the following sensitive issues.
</P>
<P>
First, the Security Council will discuss how to respond to the
military action against a sovereign country.
</P>
<P>
Sergey Lavrov, Russian permanent representative to the United
Nations, has had a draft presidential statement circulated among
council members, saying that the Security Council should take
action on the military action, which he said lacked legal
justifications. The draft called on the Security Council to lash
out at the military strikes.
</P>
<P>
China, France and Russia, three permanent members who had vote
power on the Security Council, are all against the military
action. At the same time, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who
responded to the military action by saying "This is a sad day for
the United Nations and for the world," said that he would think
about it "the morning after."
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the Security Council is expected to hold
consultations on the future arms inspections in Iraq. The
U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM), currently headed by Butler, is
in charge of disarming the Middle East country. In reality, at
issue is whether Butler should be sacked.
</P>
<P>
In his report to Annan, Butler said that Baghdad failed to
offer full cooperation with U.N. arms inspections. The report,
used by Washington as the main excuse to launch the attacks, met
with strong criticism from representatives of China and Russia who
said the Security Council that the report is one-sided and not
factual. Lavrov even took a step further to openly demand Butler
be replaced.
</P>
<P>
Butler shared his report with the U.S. government before it
"was formally delivered" to the U.N. secretary-general and the
Security Council, said a report last Friday by the New York Times
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"A full two days earlier, Mr. Butler had informed
Administration officials what he intended to say in his report and
when," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the military strikes ended, France put forward a
proposal to conduct "a profound review" of the relations between
Iraq and the United Nations, including a new way to deal with the
arms verification in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, the Security Council is expected to discuss Iraq's
compliance with the relevant U.N. resolutions since last crisis
was defused in mid-November.
</P>
<P>
China and Russia have both attacked the United States and
Britain who began the military action as Iraq resumed cooperation
with UNSCOM and the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA). The
military strikes can not be justified and the U.S. statement and
Butler's conclusion on so-called Iraq's non-cooperation do not
hold water, observers said.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan is in contact with 15
Security Council members on the crisis. Meanwhile, a number of
major members in the Security Council are also in touch with the
U.N. chief about what diplomatic steps should be taken next,
U.N. officials said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
However, one point has to be kept in mind. That is, the United
States and Britain, the two permanent members of the Security
Council, are still very tough on the issue of Iraq. Therefore, it
is really no easy job for the Security Council to make an official
response to the military strikes and safeguard its authority.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaragua Police Seize 299 Kilograms of Cocaine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Some 299 kilograms of cocaine,
valued at 10 million U.S. dollars, have been seized at a border
check point in the southern province of Rivas, Nicaraguan police
announced Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The drug was discovered at dawn of Saturday when police made a
routine inspection on a truck, which came from Costa Rica and was
going to cross the Sapoa border into Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
Police seized the cocaine hidden in 299 separate packs. But the
truck driver fled while police were concentrating on their
inspection.
</P>
<P>
This was the third large drug haul captured by Nicaraguan
police this year. Police had seized 587 kilograms of cocaine in
January and 1611 kilograms in April.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that international drug gangs were using
Guatemala as a transit point for drug transportation, and drug
trafficking has been rampant along the Panama-Costa Rica-Guatemala
route in recent years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
