<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Change Way Of Addressing Family Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The farmers of northwest
China's vast Loess Plateau have changed the way they address
family members and relatives to conform to popular changes in
cities.
</P>
<P>
Wang Haizhong, the 40-year-old head of the village of Tiancha
in Gansu Province, still calls his father "da" (a colloquialism in
the northwestern part China) as do most middle aged or older
farmers, but he has asked his son and daughter to call him "papa"
instead.
</P>
<P>
With the growth of education in rural areas and the influence
of the media and contact between rural and urban areas, more
farmers have changed the way they call their family members and
relatives.
</P>
<P>
The way husbands and wives address each other has become more
equal and civilized. In the past, farmers called their wives
"wuliren" (woman of the house), "poniang", (woman) or "mother of
my children", and the woman called her husband "zhangguide' (head
of the family), "man" or "father of my children".
</P>
<P>
Now, however, couples under 40 often replace the traditional
form with "husband" or "wife", or even calling each other
"laogong" and "laopo" or nicknames favored by urbanites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Silk Is 5,500 Years Old </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists and
textile experts say that they have discovered scraps of silk
dating back 5,500 years in central China's Henan Province.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists from the Zhengzhou Archaeological Research
Institute say that this pushes the history of Chinese silk back
1,000 years. Silk with a 4,500-year history has been found
previously in east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Songlin, a research associate at the institute says that
the silk items were discovered with more than 2,000 relics
unearthed in Xingyang, 40 kilometers away from the capital of
Zhengzhou. Archaeologists found pottery coffins for infants with
grey-white and grey-brown scraps of silk.
</P>
<P>
Scholars at the Shanghai Textile Research Institute say that
although the scraps of silk are 5,500 years old, they still have
the sheen of ordinary silk fibre.
</P>
<P>
The other relics included pottery and stone tools, pottery
knives, and bone needles. The archaeologists say that this is
evidence of China silk production early in the New Stone Age.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Calls for Adjustment of EU Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 20 (Xinhua) -- The European Union needs to
adjust its foreign policy and security arrangements following the
members' dissonant views on the U.S.-British strikes on Iraq,
Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Foreign Affairs Committee of the Lower
House, Dini said Europe's dissonant views about the strikes and
EU's collective silence have highlighted an "emergency."
</P>
<P>
The justifications for the U.S.-British operation "Desert Fox"
against Iraq were debatable, he said.
</P>
<P>
Dini believed that London's participation in the U.S.-led air
attacks on Iraq constituted a clear choice of putting Britain's
relationship with Washington over its ties with the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Britain's choice came just a few days after an Anglo-French
summit in St Malo at which both sides said they looked forward to
creating a single "true and effective" identity on foreign policy
and defense, he noted.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, in the Iraqi crisis, London "acted without
taking its membership of the European Union into account."
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton announced Saturday an end to four
days of missile and bomb strikes on Iraqi targets. U.S. defense
officials said the raids had inflicted "significant damage" to
Iraq's war machine.
</P>
<P>
"Nevertheless our initial doubts remain," said Dini, who has
questioned the usefulness of the attacks in recent days and called
for dialogue.
</P>
<P>
"They were certainly not decisions taken lightly," he said,
"but they were perhaps the wrong initiatives undertaken for
reasons which are nevertheless good."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Italian Defense Minister Carlo Scognamiglio said in
Milan that Europe's dissonant response to the Iraqi crisis
illustrated the need for the European Union to quickly find unity
in foreign policy and defense matters.
</P>
<P>
"We can't complain about not being taken into consideration if
we are not ready to pay the price," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0200 </DOCNO>
