<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> From One-way Supply to Free Choices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 21 (Xinhua) -- When an elderly resident of
Shanghai, Lian Suqin, said, "Now I can make a choice," it pretty
much summed up the changes that have taken place in the lives of
Shanghai people over the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
Lian, 67, explains that, in the past, most people lived the
same life in a designated circle, but that now they can live any
way they like and they all feel good about it. Each person used to
have a fixed work unit, each family had a designated place to buy
grain, and everyone used the same brand of soap and even studied
the same books.
</P>
<P>
Sociologists point out that at that time, the people of
Shanghai lived a kind of single-supply life and couldn't imagine
that freedom of choice was possible, even in consumer goods, and
could not imagine such rapid change taking place in the market
economy.
</P>
<P>
Lian says that there are plenty of fresh vegetables even during
winter months, and now it is necessary to make a choice before
buying any vegetables.
</P>
<P>
Even cosmetics have changed, and it's no longer just Friendship
brand Vanishing Cream, but CD, Kose, and Pond's as well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0205 </DOCNO>
