<HEADLINE> Chinese Ethnic Minority Group's Clothes Generating Income </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The traditional clothing of
the Miao people in China's Yunnan Province has helped them
increase their incomes in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The "Miaozu Huajie" (Miao Ethnic Group Flower Street) in the
town of Wenshan, the capital of Wenshan Zhuang and Miao Autonomous
Prefecture, has become a place where hundreds of traditional Miao
outfits can be found for sale to people from other parts of China
or overseas.
</P>
<P>
Tao Xingshou, 52, opened a printing and dyeing mill in 1996 and
now exports 300 to 500 pieces of Miao clothing annually to Europe,
America, and Southeast Asia, and earned more than 400,000 yuan
(48,000 U.S. dollars) in foreign exchange in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Wenshan now has 100 such plants.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 7 million Miao, 380,000 of them living in
the Wenshan Zhuang and Miao Autonomous Prefecture. Miao women are
known for their spinning, weaving, wax printing, and beautiful
brightly-colored dresses.
</P>
<P>
More than 20,000 pieces of traditional Miao clothing were
exported between April 1993 and September 1998, bringing in more
than 2 million U.S. dollars worth of funds, according to the Post
and Telecommunications Office of Wenshan prefecture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
