<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0130 GMT, December 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Nizar Hamdoon, Iraq's ambassador to the
United Nations, said Sunday that the U.S.-led military strikes
against Iraq killed or wounded thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Hamdoon said, "there has been enormous
damage, mainly to the civilian infrastructure and to human life. I
am told that the casualties are in thousands, in terms of people
who were killed or wounded. But we do not have any final figures."
</P>
<P>
Hamdoon said Iraq would ask the United Nations Security Council
to lift immediately the economic sanctions which had been in place
for eight years. (UN-Iraq-Casualties)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia objects to the turning of the U.S.-British
military action against Iraq into "a rule of international
conduct," Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations should make an assessment of the U.S. and
British missile strikes on Iraq, Ivanov said in an interview with
the Russian Public RTR TV company on the Zerkalo (Mirror) program.
(Russia-Ivanov-Iraq)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- Sierra Leone rebels of the Revolutionary United Front
have captured the diamond city of Koidu in the east of the country
following fierce fightings with the west African peace-keeping
force, ECOMOG, since last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here Sunday quoted ECOMOG officers in capital
Freetown as saying that "we could have beaten the rebels back but
it would have resulted in the loss of many civilian lives. We are
giving the civilians a few days to leave the town, then we will
strike and crush the rebels." (SLeone-Rebels-City)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin Sunday issued a
statement in connection with the end to bombing Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said that "the common sense has finally won, and the
international community should draw serious conclusions from the
tragic events," the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
(Russia-Yeltsin-Duma-Iraq)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein Sunday said that the
Iraqi people had come out victorious despite U.S. and British
military strikes during the past four days on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In a short speech read over Iraqi TV Sunday evening, Saddam
Hussein praised the Iraqi people for their steadfastness when
facing the U.S.-British air strikes.
</P>
<P>
In his first public appearance after the U.S. and Britain
announced the end to the four-day Operation Desert Fox, Saddam
praised Iraqi people's brave stance "to face American-British
aggression," saying "this stance proved to the world the essence
of Iraqi people." (Saddam-Speech-Victory)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq on Sunday refuted claims made by British Prime
Minister Tony Blair that Britain and the U.S. tried to observe
feelings of Muslims throughout the four days of air strikes
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency quoted an Information Ministry spokesman
as saying that "Blair and his master (U.S. President Bill) Clinton
had despised feelings of Muslims by not respecting traditions of
the holy month of Ramadan." (Iraq-Blair)

