<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Expecting High Growth in Offshore Banking Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The booming financial center
of Shenzen in south China is forecasting that by the end of this
year it will have enjoyed a 20 percent growth rate of its offshore
banking business, while bankers in other Asian countries are
suffering a lacklustre period because of the Asian financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen has five of China's six banks authorized to handle
offshore foreign currency transactions. They reported 2.3 billion
U.S. dollars of outstanding offshore deposits in total at the
beginning of this year and more than 2 billion dollars of
outstanding loans, up 24.9 percent and 23.7 percent respectively
on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
"This year, the business has retained its growth momentum and
we predict a sustained increase for the next year," said Li
Danming, a policy adviser in Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the city has learned the framework of its
offshore banking operations from Hong Kong, and now hopes to take
advantage of its proximity to the international financial center
to enlarge its market share.
</P>
<P>
Li has been involved in a government scheme for assessing the
possibility of making one or two Chinese banks specialists in
offshore foreign currency trading.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the success of an offshore banking center
depends largely on its attraction to foreign financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
On this point, Shenzhen has shown its potential, Li said. It is
now a home to 27 overseas financial institutions and 21 overseas
financial representative offices from 12 countries and
regions. Their combined financial asset value has accounted for a
quarter of the city's total foreign currency assets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
