<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Abandon Traditional Mail Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 21 (Xinhua) --As a result of the burgeoning
superhighway and modern telecommunications Chinese people are
sending fewer letters by traditional post and turning instead to
faxes, phone calls and increasingly e.mails.
</P>
<P>
China Business Daily reports that the amount of postal
letters was down by 12.8 percent in 1997 from the previous year
and dipped even further during the first quarter of this year by
another 2.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report said that 55 percent of mailed letters are private
with 40 percent from the business sector or printed material.
</P>
<P>
However, it went on to urge Chinese companies to use the postal
service while saying that in advanced countries, 90 percent of the
mail is printed material.
</P>
<P>
But a recent survey discovered that large companies, which are
less inclined to use printed materials, prefer radio, TV and
newspapers for marketing their products and services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Telegram Business Decreasing But It's Not Dead Yet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The telegram business is
shrinking because of more modern means of telecommunications like
mobile phones, faxes, and e-mail, Guangming Daily reports.
</P>
<P>
Telegrams have been losing ground since 1985. Before that, 3
million telegrams used to bring in half of Beijing Telecom's
revenues monthly. That number plunged to just over 400,000 a month
by 1996, and just over 4,000 a month in October of this year.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper reports that more than half of the people in
telegram offices have found other kinds of work.
</P>
<P>
Yang Cuiping, chief of the telecommunications section of the
Yong'an Road Post Office in eastern Beijing, told the newspaper
that the telegram business has shrunk 30 percent annually over the
past decade. She says that during the '80s, the office sent 1,200
telegrams a day but the daily record is now only around 50, and
their telegram employees have gone from over 50 people to around
10.
</P>
<P>
However, Yang says, the telegram business is not going to die
out in the foreseeable future in China because some remote and
mountainous areas don't have access to modern telecommunications
facilities and still rely on telegrams.
</P>
<P>
The old business is also trying to adopt new methods and has
come up with "courtesy telegrams" for New Year's, birthday, and
marriage celebrations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981221.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africans Win World Cross-Country Challenge Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Two African runners won on
Sunday the first World Cross-Country Challenge races for the
1998-1999 season.
</P>
<P>
Limo Richard, a 25-year-old Kenyan running his first World
Cup, won the 10,500-meter race in a time of 32 minutes 14
seconds. Mekonnen Haylu of Ethiopia and Koech Paul of Kenya
finished second and third in the race with clockings of 32:15 and
32:17 respectively.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 runners from 26 countries competed in the men's
race while more than 60 women from 17 countries competed in a
6,000-meter race of their own, of which Wami Gete of Ethiopia won
in 20:17.
</P>
<P>
Eight seconds adrift at 20:25 was Sandell Annemarie of Finland
while Worku Ayelech of Ethiopia came home third in 20:34.
</P>
<P>
Limo told the press after the race that he felt a bit pushy in
his left hip joint while running the race and that it may be
caused by his nervousness in his first major event and his first
race in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Unlike last year's event that was held in chilly rains, this
year's race was held in an unusual sunny weather for Sunday's
crowd of thousands.
</P>
<P>
This season's World Cross-Country Challenge series will later
take place in Aurham of Britain, Chiba of Japan, Mombasa of
Kenya, Vilamora of Portugal, Sevilla of Spain and Belfast of Nort
hern Ireland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
